Commentary.Commentary: We are back for the second innings. South Africa players stride out to the middle. Followed by Alex Lees and Zak Crawley who walk out to open for England. There is sun peeking now from the skies. Not the sight any South Africa player would like. keeping in mind the conditions they dealt with in the morning session. It will be Kagiso Rabada to start with the new ball.
... SECOND INNINGS ...

The English pacers were on song from the word go and once Ollie Robinson got that first breakthrough, they started to send back one batter after the another. With the opposition at 36/6, one would have thought that the hosts will bundle them out for a score of under 100 runs but that wasn't the case. Stuart Broad was excellent with the ball in the post-Lunch session which helped them to get rid of the tail quickly. In the end, though, they will take 118 runs and it is now up to their batters to try and get a big first innings lead. But will they be able to do so? Find out soon as the English first innings is coming up shortly.

The conditions did favor the pacers and South Africa did not have many batters in the lineup who had the experience of playing Test cricket in England and it showed. The skipper, Dean Elgar though will be disappointed as he was the first to fall and that set the tone for those who followed. Only the stand between Khaya Zondo and Marco Jansen for the 7th wicket was a positive with the bat for the Proteas and Keshav Maharaj too did well to muster up a few runs. They will now have to come out all guns blazing if they are to make a match out of it.

It has been a comprehensive performance by the English pacers on Day 3 of the third Test match and the inexperienced South African batters have had no answers. England will come out to bat much earlier than they would have expected but will be happy about it. Also, Ollie Robinson leads the English players off the field with his five-wicket haul.

OUT! CAUGHT! Stuart Broad ends his innings with a four-fer. It is a full-length ball, on off stump. Anrich Nortje ends up slicing it towards covers. Ben Stokes takes the simplest of catches to bundle out South Africa for just 118 here. A forgetful innings for South Africa.
Commentary.Howout: c Ben Stokes b Stuart Broad

Commentary.Commentary: FOUR! Edge over the fielder at third slip. That was short, outside off. Anrich Nortje goes hard at the ball but gets an outside edge and the ball travels over the slips for a boundary.
Anrich Nortje finally opens his account. It is fuller, outside off. Nortje drives it past short extra cover. The batters take three before the fielder cuts it out.
Touch fuller, around off. Anrich Nortje pushes it gently towards covers. Does not get any run off it.
Make that three! This one is a short ball, on leg. Anrich Nortje ducks under it wisely.
Two dots in a row now! It is angled into the pads, on a fuller length, Nortje flicks it to mid-wicket.
On a length, outside off, shaping in from outside off. Nortje blocks it out on his front foot.
Robinson goes full and on off. Rabada drives it towards mid off. They take one.
A dot to end the over! Broad serves it on a length, outside off, nipping into the batter. Anrich Nortje stays back, closes the face of his blade and blocks it out.
Anrich Nortje is the last man in for South Africa.

OUT! TIMBER! Stuart Broad gets his third wicket. Back of length, around fourth stump. Keshav Maharaj clears his front leg and goes for the pull but he gets a bottom edge. The ball goes onto shatter the stumps. Stuart Broad is in a hurry to end things here.
Commentary.Howout: b Stuart Broad

Commentary.Commentary: Full length, on middle and leg. Rabada flicks it to deep mid-wicket for three runs now.
Fuller length, outside off. Kagiso Rabada drives it off the front foot but he was not in complete control and the ball hits the outside half of the bat. The ball goes towards point for a couple.
On a good length, angling in. Kagiso Rabada tries to play it towards off but gets a leading edge and the ball just falling short of mid-on.
Stuart Broad start round the wicket. That was fuller, around off. Kagiso Rabada blocks back to the bowler.
Maharaj flicks it to deep square leg and the batters take two.
Short ball, on off. Maharaj makes some room and flat-bats it over the bowler's head. Two taken this time.
NO BALL! Full length, outside off. Maharaj looks to chase it but gets beaten this time. The crowd is getting into the act as well now. It is a no ball as the bowler oversteps.
A short ball, on off. Keshav Maharaj makes some room and cuts it hard to the man at backward point.
Full length, angled into the pads. Rabada flicks it to deep square leg. The batters take a single and 100 is up for South Africa.
Kagiso Rabada is the new man in.

OUT! CAUGHT! There it is, a five-wicket haul for Ollie Robinson and it has been a superb spell from him. Robinson serves it full and around off, inviting the drive from the batter. Marco Jansen does go for it and this time the outside edge is found. The ball goes quickly and straight into the bread basket as Joe Root takes a sharp catch at first slip. Jansen's important contribution comes to an end and South Africa are now eighth down.
Commentary.Howout: c Joe Root b Ollie Robinson

Commentary.Commentary: Good length, around off and Jansen plays inside the line of the ball.
On a good length, swinging away from Keshav Maharaj. That ball just missed the off-pole.
Short of length, down the leg. Keshav Maharaj lets that ball go through to the keeper.
Fuller delivery, onto off. Keshav Maharaj pushes it towards mid-on for no run.
Fuller length, outside off. Keshav Maharaj lets that ball goes through to the keeper.
Short, around middle stump. Keshav Maharaj tries to pull that one but misses it.
Fuller length, angling in. Keshav Maharaj knocks it towards silly mid-on.
Pitched up in the channel around off, Jansen looks for the cover drive but gets beaten past the outside edge yet again.
On a hard length, around off and nipping back in. Jansen stays on the back foot and solidly keeps it out.
Good length, outside off and the ball just straightens off the deck. Jansen has a dab at it but the ball goes past the outside edge.
Just short! Banged in short and over leg stump this time. Keshav Maharaj goes after it and the ball goes off the top edge and on the bounce to the man at deep square leg. Single taken.
FOUR! Well played! A bit of a long hop by Robinson, around off. Keshav Maharaj pulls it away, the ball goes aerially and in front of square for a boundary.
Full and straight, clipped away behind square on the leg side for a single.
On a good length, around off. Keshav Maharaj blocks it solidly from the crease.
Fuller length, down the leg. Keshav Maharaj lets that ball go through to the keeper.
On a good length, around off. Keshav Maharaj pushes it towards point for no run.
Beautiful delivery by Stuart Broad. That was on a good length, angling in. Keshav Maharaj tries to block that one but the ball goes through to the keeper between bat and pad.
FOUR! No need to run! That was short, outside off. Keshav Maharaj cuts it through the point region for an easy boundary.
On a good length, angling in. Keshav Maharaj tries to work it towards mid-wicket but misses it and the ball hits his pads.
Another short ball, around off, Marco Jansen gets well behind it and keeps it down on the off side.
Another bouncer, this time around off and Jansen gets comfortably underneath it.
NO BALL! Robinson goes for the bumper now and over middle and leg, Jansen ducks under it well. A no ball though has been called but for overstepping.
FOUR! Top shot! Very full and on off, Marco Jansen drives it straight back past the bowler and picks up a boundary.
Around the top of off, Jansen defends it out from his crease.
Length ball, around the fifth stump line, Jansen shoulders arms at it.
Nagging length, around off, Keshav Maharaj looks to play it off the back foot but ends up chopping it past the stumps. The ball goes towards backward square leg and they get a single.
Around middle, kept out by Jansen.

Edged and four! Full again from Broad, around off and inviting the drive. Marco Jansen goes for the cover drive once again and once again the outside edge is found. Ollie Pope at fourth slip dives low to his left and fails to grab it as the ball runs away to the fence. Two chances dropped in the very same over and Jansen's stay at the crease isn't over yet.
Length again, outside off and Jansen makes an easy leave.
Good length, around off, pushed away towards cover.

Edged and dropped! Pitched up, outside off and out comes the cover drive. Jansen gets a faint outside edge on it and the keeper, Ben Foakes dives to his right. The ball does wobble a bit and late as well and Foakes ends up spilling it.
On the shorter side and over off stump, Jansen solidly defends it out.
Robinson pushes this one wider of the off stump, Maharaj lets it through to the keeper.
Around middle, Maharaj gets across and tucks it away down to fine leg for a couple of runs. With that, Keshav Maharaj brings up 1000 runs in Test cricket.
Back of a length, around off and played off the back foot towards cover.
Around the top of off, played back to the bowler.
Well left! Length ball, close to the off stump and Maharaj judges the length to perfection as he makes the leave. The ball goes over off stump and is collected by the keeper.
Fuller length, on leg stump and this is flicked away to short mid-wicket.

Half an appeal but there's no bat on that one. Good length, around off and the ball nips back in off the surface. Marco Jansen gets squared up and the ball goes off the thigh pads and into the hands of the man at first slip.
Length ball, around middle, defended onto the leg side.
Goes fuller now, on off stump and blocked towards short mid-wicket for a quick run.
Back of a length and on off, Maharaj goes on the back foot to play it towards mid on.
Good length again, angling it into the pads. Keshav Maharaj looks to work it leg side but misses and gets hit on top of his pads.
Good length, around off, Maharaj gets pushed on the back foot and gets an inside edge onto the pads as he looks to punch it away.
Play and a miss! Pitched up, around off and Jansen goes for the booming drive this time. Luckily for him, the ball beats the outside edge.
Full and straight, Maharaj punches it straight back past the bowler and to the left of mid on. The batters scamper across for one as Stuart Broad at mid on tidies up.
Good length, angling it into the body, Keshav Maharaj looks to play at it but misses and gets hit on the thigh pads.
Excellent running! Robinson keeps it fuller and around off, Jansen leans forward and just pushes it out towards short extra cover for a quick single.
Nicely driven! Pitched up around off, Marco Jansen plays a beautiful cover drive but the ball just slows up due to the sluggish outfield and Jansen picks up a couple of runs.
Robinson starts off with a fullish delivery, well outside off and it is left alone by Jansen.
Keshav Maharaj is the new man in. Also, it will be Ollie Robinson to bowl from the other end.

OUT! CAUGHT! Extra bounce from Stuart Broad and the useful stand is broken right away after the interval. Broad digs it in a bit short and around off, the ball shoots up off the deck. Khaya Zondo is batting outside his crease and gets hurried on and the ball takes the shoulder of the bat. The ball pops up around the gully region where Alex Lees takes a simple catch. Zondo's resistance is over and South Africa lose their 7th wicket.
Commentary.Howout: c Alex Lees b Stuart Broad

Commentary.Commentary: Length ball, around off and nipping in off the deck. Zondo defends it out.
Full and wide this time, nicely driven through cover-point for a couple of runs.
Broad keeps it full and on off stump, blocked out by Zondo.

Stuart Broad goes full and angles it into the pads. Khaya Zondo gets stuck on the crease and looks to play it through mid-wicket. Zondio misses and gets hit on the pads. There is a huge appeal for LBW and this time it is given. Khaya Zondo has a chat with Marco Jansen and does go for the review. UltraEdge confirms that there's no bat involved and Ball Tracking shows that the ball is sliding down the leg side, missing the stumps. A good review by Zondo and he survives.

A good use of the review by Khaya Zondo here. He was pretty confident while taking the review and it pays off here. South Africa still have all the reviews in their kitty, unlike England who just have a single left.
Runs straightaway after Lunch! Broad starts off with a fullish delivery on the pads, Marco Jansen flicks it 'round the corner for a single.

We are back for the afternoon session. The two umpires make their way out to the middle. Marco Jansen and Khaya Zondo are out of the dressing room and striding towards the crease. Soon, the England players also gather nears the ropes before they take the field. It will be Stuart Broad to start with the ball. Four slips waiting for the outside edge. Here we go...
... Day 3, Session 2 ...

So, two days ago England opted to bowl and the bowlers have justified their skipper's decision. It was certainly a fine display of seam bowling this morning session by the English pacers. Ollie Robinson was on song from the word go. He picked up four wickets in no time. James Anderson and Stuart Broad chipped in with a wicket each as well. Jack Leach leaked a few runs in his short spell right at the fag end of the session. England would be hoping to get back on the field and get rid of the opposition tail as soon as possible. Do join us at 6.10 pm IST (12.40 pm GMT) to find out how things pan out in the post-Lunch session.

South Africa were nowhere near their potential this morning. Their batters just did not turn up to the game. The top-order nicked almost everything this morning which saw South Africa teetering at 36/6. The conundrum for Marco Jansen and Khaya Zondo, who was playing his first ever Test match, was mostly of how they approach the game forward. They decided to stop chasing after all the ball and capitalize on the few bad ones on offer. The doughty pair put up a stand on of 33 runs to remain unbeaten at Lunch. They still have a huge task ahead of them as they come back out in a short while to make it better for the visitors.

In a spine-tingling atmosphere across the United Kingdom, England were able to put up an exhilarating performance at the Oval to put them in the driving seat in this encounter. The morning session truly belonged to the hosts as South Africa were dismantled with the new ball.
Fullish length, a bit wider and shaping in late. Khaya Zondo leaves it alone and it will be a maiden to conclude the morning session on Day 3. The umpires signal for Lunch!
Fuller length, outside off. Khaya Zondo plays it towards mid-off for no run.
Fuller length, around off. Khaya Zondo plays it towards the point.
On a good length, on off pole. Khaya Zondo defends it off the front foot and gets an outside edge and the ball just falls short of the slip fielder.
Fuller length, outside off. Khaya Zondo raises his arm and leaves it.
On a good length, outside off. Khaya Zondo lets that one go through to the keeper.
Nicely bowled and well left as well. Fuller and close to the off pole, inviting the lofted shot but Jansen just leaves it alone. Maiden!
On middle and leg, kept out on the leg side.
Tosses it up a bit now and pushes it wider. Marco Jansen drives it with the turn but straight towards short cover.
On a length and on off, Jansen defends it back onto the deck.
A touch fuller and around off, defended with gentle hands towards point.
On a nagging length and in that channel around off, Marco Jansen shoulders his arms.
On a good length, outside off. Khaya Zondo lets that one go through to the keeper.
On a good length, outside off. Khaya Zondo blocks it off the front foot.
On a good length, angling in. Marco Jansen gets an inside edge and the ball goes towards the square leg for a single.
James Anderson bowls this one fuller, outside off. Marco Jansen drives it through cover for a couple of runs.
Short of length, outside off. Marco Jansen pushes it towards the point fielder.
On a good length, angling in, onto the pads. Marco Jansen tries to play it towards mid-wicket but misses it.
Floated up, full and around off, Zondo defends it out with soft hands.
FOUR! Short and wide, duly punished. Leach drops it short and around off, Khaya Zondo rocks back and cuts it behind point for a boundary.
Flatter one, on off, Zondo solidly keeps it out.
SIX! Excellent use of the feet by Khaya Zondo! Tossed up on middle, Zondo skips down the track and just times the lofted shot back over the bowler's head for a biggie.
A bit quicker and on off, Zondo taps it out and onto the off side.
Starts off with a fullish delivery on middle, Khaya Zondo gets forward to defend.
Change. Jack Leach comes into the attack now for the first time in the morning session.
On a good length, onto the middle stump. Khaya Zondo tries to work it towards mid-wicket but gets a leading edge and the ball goes towards cover and a single is being taken.
Fuller length, outside off. Khaya Zondo tries to go aerial from the crease but didn't connect.
Play and a miss. James Anderson bowls it fuller, outside off. Khaya Zondo tries to drive it through covers but misses it.
On a god length, around off. Khaya Zondo plays it towards cover.
Fuller length, outside off. Khaya Zondo raises his hands and lets them go to the keeper.
Fuller length, outside off. Khaya Zondo lets that ball go through to the keeper.
On the pads, this is clipped away through square leg for a single.

Full and angling onto the pads, Zondo looks to flick but misses and the ball pings him on the pads. Stuart Broad goes up in appeal for LBW but it is turned down. The English players think about it but eventually, the review isn't taken and rightly so.
Very full and around middle, this is defended back towards the bowler.
A touch fuller and attacking middle stump, Zondo gets across well and defends it out.
Length again, on the fifth stump line and this time Khaya Zondo just plays inside the line of the ball.
Good length, around the top of off and solidly kept out on the off side by Zondo.
Fuller length, onto the leg stump. Marco Jansen plays it towards mid off.

A huge appeal by James Anderson but the umpire doesn't seem interested. That was full, angling in. Marco Jansen misses getting the bat to it and the ball hits the front pad but the replay shows that the ball is missing to hit the leg stump.
Fuller length, around off. Marco Jansen blocks it back to the bowler.
Fuller length, around leg stump. Marco Jansen tries to play it towards mid-wicket but gets a leading edge and the ball goes towards covers.
On a good length, around off. Marco Jansen blocks it from the front foot.
Fuller length, around off. Marco Jansen tries to defend it but gets an inside edge and the ball just falls short of slip.
Change. James Anderson (4-0-12-1) is back into the attack now. The ball is still moving ferociously in these helpful conditions. Can James Anderson break this stand?
Beaten! Pitched up, around off and this time the ball leaves the right-hander. Khaya Zondo looks to drive at it but gets beaten past the outside edge.
Good length, around off and nipping in off the surface. The ball stays a touch low and Zondo does well to get some bat on it.
Just a tad shorter and around middle, Zondo neatly tucks it away past square leg and picks up a couple of runs.
Good length, drifted down the leg side, Zondo leaves it alone.
A huge dark cloud is making its way towards the stadium. It is not a really good sight to be honest.
Inside edge! Fuller and a bit quicker, angling into the off stump, Khaya Zondo gets a thick inside edge onto the pads as he looks to block it out.
Broad goes a bit wider of the crease and angles it around off stump. The ball straightens after pitching and beats the outside edge.
On a good length, outside off. Marco Jansen lets that ball go through to the keeper.
On a good length, outside off. Marco Jansen gets beaten by the swing and the ball goes through to the keeper.
Fuller length, on off. Marco Jansen blocks it off the front foot.

FOOUR! Classic on drive! That was full, onto the middle stump. Marco Jansen shows the full face of the bat and plays it straight past the stumps for a boundary. This also brings up 50 for South Africa in style. They have something to cheer about.
Surprise short ball. Ollie Robinson bowls it quicker onto the body. Marco Jansen tries to duck this one but he gets hit on the elbow and the ball goes through to the keeper.
Fuller length, outside off. Marco Jansen lets that one go through to the keeper.

Good length, on off and angling in sharply. Khaya Zondo gets squared up and has to hop to keep it out. Zondo misses and the ball thuds into the pads. There is an appeal for LBW but it is turned down. Ben Stokes has a chat with his players and he has gone for the review. On first look, there seems to be no bat involved and the third umpire goes straight to Ball Tracking. It is confirmed that the ball is going over leg stump and they have now lost their second review.
Another good shot by Marco Jansen. Full and on the pads, worked away by Jansen through mid-wicket. Jack Leach from behind square on the leg side runs around to his left and keeps it down to three.
Lovely! Perfect length, tighter on off stump, Jansen looks to defend but the ball zips past the outside edge.
FOUR! Nicely worked away. On the pads, Jansen flicks it away in front of mid-wicket and the ball runs away into the fence.
Play and a miss! Full and outside off, shaping away a touch. Marco Jansen looks to push it out towards covers but gets beaten past the outside edge.
This is a bit fuller and angled into off stump, Jansen pushes it off the front foot and towards mid on.
Fuller length, on off. Khaya Zondo knocks it towards silly mid-off.
On a good length, outside off. Khaya Zondo tries to play it towards cover but misses it.
Fuller length, angling in. Khaya Zondo knocks it towards short mid-wicket.
Tad fuller, on off. Marco Jansen punches it towards mid-on for a quick single.
Fuller length, around the middle. Marco Jansen punches it towards mid on and a couple of runs are being taken.
Short of length, around pads. The ball hits his pads and rolls towards short square leg for a leg bye single.
Full and wide, shaping away, Marco Jansen looks for the cover drive but misses.
Good length, around off, Jansen defends this one off the front foot.

Stuart Broad goes full and bowls it on off. The ball nips back in sharply, going through the defence and in between bat and pad. There is a noise as the keeper catches the ball and there is a huge appeal for caught behind but it has been turned down! Ben Stokes opts for the review almost instantly. The third umpire checks UltraEdge first and it shows up a flat line as the ball passes the bat. The LBW is also checked but the ball missed the pads as well. NOT OUT!
Broad slides one down the leg side, Jansen looks to get a fine tickle on it but misses.
Length again, angling onto the pads, Zondo tucks it away past square leg for a single.
Length ball, a bit wide of the off stump. Khaya Zondo looks to play at it but then pulls out of the shot.

BEATEN! A gem of a delivery to end the over and it is a wicket-maiden! Robinson serves it a bit fuller and in that channel around off, the ball nips away off the surface. Marco Jansen looks to defend but is beaten past the outside edge.
Marco Jansen is the new man in.

OUT! CAUGHT BEHIND! Not the greatest of shots by Wiaan Mulder. That ball was full, outside off. Wiaan Mulder plays a half-hearted shot towards cover but the ball is swinging away. Mulder gets an outside edge and the ball is pouched comfortably by Ben Foakes. Simplest of catches. South Africa is in deep trouble.
Commentary.Howout: c Ben Foakes b Ollie Robinson

Commentary.Commentary: On a good length, outside off. Wiaan Mulder let that ball go through to the keeper.
Fuller this time, outside off. Wiaan Mulder leaves that ball alone.
Short of length, around off. Wiaan Mulder lets that ball go through to the keeper.
On a good length, around off. Wiaan Mulder pushes it towards the short leg.

Drinks break! The first hour has completely belonged to England and one man in particular, Ollie Robinson. Robinson has been immaculate with his lines and lengths and has picked up 3 wickets with Anderson and Broad chipping in with one each. South Africa have just not shown up yet and have paid the price for some nervy batting. Khaya Zondo and Wiaan Mulder, the last recognized pair is at the crease and will hope to get them out of this hole and to a decent total.
Pitched up on middle, this is pushed away towards mid on for an easy single.
Nicely played! Full and outside off, at 140 clicks. Wiaan Mulder waits for it and plays it under his eye line, behind point and for a couple of runs.
A bit of swing there but the line is not the correct one. Length ball, well outside off and shaping further away, no shot offered by Mulder.
Broad goes shorter now and serves it outside off, Mulder looks to have a go at it but pulls out of his shot in the end.
Very full and well outside off, Wiaan Mulder leaves it alone.
Broad pitches it around the off stump and angles it in. Khaya Zondo has a tentative push at it and manages to get it past point for a single.
A successful over by Robinson comes to an end. It is full and on off. Mulder blocks it out watchfully.
Angles it in, full and on off. Mulder defends it into the deck.
Length ball, on middle and leg, blocked to the leg side.
Wiaan Mulder is the new man in.

OUT! CAUGHT BEHIND! Ollie Robinson is on fire here. He gets his third wicket now. Kyle Verreynne is the target this who has been hunted down by Robinson. This man is on a mission. Robinson serves a length ball, around off. It nips away a touch of the deck. It enough to get some wood on the way. Kyle Verreynne outside-edges it to Ben Foakes, who takes it with ease.
Commentary.Howout: c Ben Foakes b Ollie Robinson

Commentary.Commentary: Length ball, on off, defended out solidly.
LEG BYE! A length ball, angled into the pads. Zondo looks to tuck it away but misses. It hits him on his thigh pads and goes past the diving fielder at short leg. They collect a leg bye.
Kyle Verreynne walks in at number 6.

OUT! CAUGHT BEHIND! Ryan Rickelton does not even wait for the decision and walks back instantly. Stuart Broad serves it full and on off, this one is angling across the left-hander. Ryan Rickelton looks to defend it out but only gets a thick outside edge. It carries to Ben Foakes behind the sticks who makes no mistake. Stuart Broad gets his first wicket here. South Africa lose 4 wickets inside the first hour of play in the morning session.
Commentary.Howout: c Ben Foakes b Stuart Broad

Commentary.Commentary: FOUR! Nicely played! It is a length ball, outside off. Ryan Rickelton stays back and punches it past gully. The ball races away to the boundary.
This one is angled into the pads, Zondo tucks it to square leg and gets across for a single.
Swing and a miss! Broad goes short this time, outside off. It nips in a touch off the deck. Zondo hangs back and looks to cut it away but only connects with thin air.
Outside off, yet again. Zondo gets behind and defends it out watchfully.
Broad starts with a good-length ball, wide of off. Zondo shuffles across and blocks it out.
Stuart Broad comes in as first change now.
Beaten again! It is a length ball, around off, angling across the left-hander. Ryan Rickelton looks to defend it out on his front foot but gets beaten on the outside edge.
Make that 5 now! It is on a good length, around off, shaping away with the angle. Ryan Rickelton looks to push it away but misses.
Length ball, on off, blocked out. Four dots in a row now. Excellent from Ollie Robinson.
This time Robinson goes full and on off. Ryan Rickelton gets an inside edge onto his pads. Joe Root is seen appealing for lbw from the slip cordon but Ollie Robinson shows no interest.
It is a length ball, around off, shaping away a touch. Ryan Rickelton stays inside the crease and shoulders his arms at it.
Ollie Robinson stays over the wicket for the left-hander this time. It is angled across the left-hander, full and outside off. Ryan Rickelton has no shot to offer.
A tidy over by James Anderson comes to an end. It is a length ball, on fifth stump, holds its line this time. Khaya Zondo shuffles across and shoulders his arms at it.
Good length, outside off, left alone by Zondo.
On off, blocked out solidly.
A length ball, on off. Zondo strokes it past backward point. They take two.
Full length, on off. Ryan Rickelton taps it to mid off for a quick single.

Risky single this time! It is full, on off. Zondo bocks it out to covers. Alex Lees is quick to get to the ball, as the batters decide to take a single. Ryan Rickelton puts in a dive to get inside the crease, although the effort of Lees missed the stumps at the striker's end.
Good length, outside off. Zondo taps it to point for one.

EDGED but does not carry! Ollie Robinson is on fire here! It is a length ball, on off. Khaya Zondo shuffles across and looks to block it out. It takes the outside edge and goes towards the slip cordon. It lands short of the fielder though at second slip who collets it on a bounce.
Khaya Zondo walks in with South Africa in a spot of bother. Five slips put in place.

OUT! TIMBER! Top of off stump yet again for Ollie Robinson. He has been magnificent this morning. Ollie Robinson hurls it on a length, outside off. Keegan Petersen thinks that this will hold its line and shoulders his arms at it. Although, he was left shook, as he stared at the disturbed stumps as the ball nips back in sharply off the deck and hits the top of off. Keegan Petersen trudges back to the pavilion. South Africa are in a spot of bother.
Commentary.Howout: b Ollie Robinson

Commentary.Commentary: Fraction short, outside off, left alone.
FOUR! Incredible shot! It is much fuller this time, outside off. Keegan Petersen frees his arms and drives it through backward point for a boundary.
An inswinger, full and on off. Keegan Petersen blocks it out to short extra cover.
Four dots on the trot to end the over! It is a length ball, on off. Ryan Rickelton blocks it to the off side.
Length on off, Ryan Rickelton shuffles and tucks it to mid-wicket.
BEAUTY! It is a length ball, on off, angled across the left-hander. Ryan Rickelton looks to defend it out but gets beaten on the outside edge.
Fuller, outside off, leaving the batter this time. Ryan Rickelton shoudlers his arms at it.
Good-length ball, in the channel. Keegan Petersen hops and taps it out to covers. They take one more.
Anderson goes full and on off. It nips in a touch off the deck. Ryan Rickelton gets an inside edge onto his pads. It rolls out to covers and the batters scamper through for a single.
A single to end the over! Fuller, on off. Ryan Rickelton dabs it to covers and gets across for one.
Robinson comes 'round the wicket now. It is fuller, angled in on off. Ryan Rickelton shuffles across and flicks it to mid-wicket.
Good running! It is a full-length ball, outside off. Keegan Petersen gets it past gully off the outer half. The batters take three before the fielder cuts it out.
This is wide of off, Keegan Petersen shoulders his arms at it.
Good-length ball, outside off. This time it nips in off the deck but not much. Keegan Petersen trusts the bounce and leaves it alone for the keeper.
Ollie Robinson comes over the wicket for the right-hander. It is fuller, angled into the pads. Keegan Petersen tucks it to the leg side.
Length ball, on middle and leg. Ryan Rickelton blocks it out solidly. A wicket-taking over by Anderson comes to an end.

FOUR! Ryan Rickelton gets off the mark in some fine fashion. This should ease the pressure for him. It is fuller, outside off. Ryan Rickelton leans in and creams it through the gap at covers for four.
Anderson goes full again, around off, does not get the ball to nip in off the deck. It is very comfortable for Ryan Rickelton to leave it alone.
A dot now! It is touch fuller, outside off, moving away with the angle. Ryan Rickelton shuffles across and leaves it alone.
Ryan Rickelton is in at number 4.

OUT! CAUGHT BEHIND! Trouble for South Africa. James Anderson gets his man now. England right on top. Sarel Erwee walks back to the pavilion on a duck. Anderson serves a length ball, around off, angled across the left-hander. Sarel Erwee hangs inside his crease and tries to have a poke at it. All he manages to get in a thick outside edge. Ben Foakes does really well to dive to his left and pouch the ball safely. Both the openers for South Africa are sent back in a jiffy.
Commentary.Howout: c Ben Foakes b James Anderson

Commentary.Commentary: On a good length, around off and moving away a touch. Peterson plays it away past point for a single.
Full and straight, Keegan Petersen clips it away in front of mid-wicket and gets off the mark with a three.
NO BALL! Good length, around off, Peterson has a little dab at it but misses. Another no ball has been called for overstepping.
A length ball, outside off and left alone for the keeper to collect.
Top delivery! Good length, around off and nipping in sharply. Keegan Petersen makes an assured leave as the ball just goes over the top of off stump.

OUT! CLEANED HIM UP! Ollie Robinson srikes in his very first over. Just the start England were after. Ollie Robinson does very well to use the angle to his benefit. He steams in from around the wicket and hurls a length ball, outside off. It nips in off the deck. Dean Elgar tries to defend it out but misses it completely. The ball sneaks through the gap between bat and pad to shatter the stumps. An early success for England.
Commentary.Howout: b Ollie Robinson

Commentary.Commentary: Ollie Robinson continues to come around the wicket. It is fuller, outside off. Elgar has no shot to offer. The umpire signals a no ball as the bowler oversteps.
This one is outside off and Elgar does not bother.
Woah! Ollie Robinson asking the right question straightaway. It is a length ball, on top of off. It holds its line off the deck. Elgar looks to push it away but gets beaten on the outside edge.
Ollie Robinson to share the new ball with James Anderson.
A great start by James Anderson. It is a length ball, outside off. Erwee presses forward and blocks it out.
Good length, outside off, left alone.
Length ball, on leg stump. Erwee gets an inside edge on his pads.
First run for Elgar and South Africa! Full length, sliding down leg. Elgar clips it to deep square leg for a single.
Good length, around off and just shaping away a touch. Dean Elgar dabs it down towards gully.
Anderson starts off with a length ball, outside off and Elgar just lets it through.

We are moments away from the start of play. The players are already on the ground and they have observed a minute's silence as well. The ground has been quiet for a while now but there goes the chime, followed by the national anthems. It will be South Africa's national anthem first followed by a rendition of 'God Save the King.'Done with the pre-game formalities and we are now ready for play. The English players make their way out to the middle followed by the South African opening pair of Dean Elgar and Sarel Erwee. James Anderson to start proceedings with the ball here.

As we patiently wait for the start of play at the Oval, a few miles to the north at St. James Palace in London, everything is being readied for the proclamation of the new King, Charles III. It will be the first televised proclamation and also the flags at the Oval will be at full mast for the entirety of the day and not at half-mast. Another thing to note is that there is a good crowd building up around the Oval and the sun is coming out as well.

In terms of actual play, there isn't much to talk about other than the toss which was won by England and Ben Stokes has put South Africa into bat. There are still grey clouds hovering over London but little to no rain is expected in the remaining 3 days and the revised playing conditions, 98 overs per day should get completed smoothly. We have seen a result in three days before and that too in this series itself, so, the game and the series still hang perfectly in balance with the shortened game making for an even more exciting watch.

Hello and welcome ladies and gentlemen to Day 3 of the third and final Test match between England and South Africa at the Oval in London. As all of the UK mourns the demise of Queen Elizabeth II, play is set to resume and will go on as per the usual timings, i.e., beginning at 3.30 pm IST (10 am GMT) but 10 minutes before the play begins, there will be a Guard of Honour, followed by a minute's silence. Then there will be a one bell chime at the Oval by the highest-ranking military before the national anthems of South Africa and England respectively.
... DAY 3, SESSION 1 ...

UPDATE 8.28 pm IST (2.58 pm GMT) - We have some news regarding the latest developments from the 3rd and deciding Test match between England and South Africa. England and Wales Cricket Board (ECB) have released a statement in which it states that the match will resume on Saturday, the 10th of September and will go on till Monday. So, it will be effectively a three-day game as South Africa have to leave for home on Tuesday. The follow-on will be reduced to 150 instead of 200 runs and before the start of play the teams will observe a minute of silence in honour of Queen Elizabeth II. Along with this, all cricketing action in the UK is set to resume as well.

Unfortunate news as Her Majesty Queen Elizabeth II has passed away. The world is mourning and condolences are pouring in from around the world. England and Wales Cricket Board has informed us that Friday's play between England and South Africa Men will not take place. The updates regarding the fixture beyond Friday will be provided in due course. We will keep you posted.
...THIRD TEST...

Well, well, well! The inevitable has happened. The rain has been persistent throughout the day and the umpires have finally concluded that the play on Day 1 has been ABANDONED. It was mostly a frustrating day for cricket. Firstly, it was the delayed toss due to the overnight rain and later, the rain gods just kept interfering throughout the day whenever it looked like we could be able to squeeze in some game time. That's it from the coverage albeit there was nothing much to cover. The health of the Queen of England is yet another concern and if anything were to happen, tomorrow's play might be called off. But there's nothing official yet and it's all speculation at the moment. We will keep you updated in this regard as well. For now, the action will continue on 9th September 2022. The first ball on Day 2 will be at 3.30 pm IST (10 am GMT). But you can join us early for the build-up. Till then take care and goodbye!
As we continue to play hide and seek with the rain in London, elsewhere in the UAE, Virat Kohli has finally ended the long, long wait for his 71st international century.

UPDATE 8.33 pm IST (3.03 pm GMT) - OH DEAR! Right on cue. Just when the inspection was scheduled the rain gods have decided to reappear. The covers are back on the field and the wait game shall go on. Still no official word on Tea yet. Stay tuned for more updates.

As we wait for the details of the next inspection, you can switch tabs and catch the action from the Asia Cup where India are playing Afghanistan and have had a brilliant start. India are currently 125/2 in 13 overs.

UPDATE 8.04 pm IST (2.34 pm GMT) - Unfortunately the wait game continues as the umpires are dissatisfied with the playing conditions. There will be another inspection at 8.30 pm IST (3 pm GMT). Hopefully, we are back with some good news. Fingers crossed!
UPDATE 7.50 pm IST (2.20 pm GMT) - The umpires are currently on the field. There is a square cover still intact. There is no rain though at the moment which is a really good sign.

UPDATE 7.14 pm IST (1.44 pm GMT) - The sun is out! But lets not get carried away. There will be an inspection at 7.40 pm IST (2.10 pm GMT). Looking at the signs it shouldn't be long before we get going. Lets hope for the best.

UPDATE 6.53 pm IST (1.23 pm GMT) - Finally some good signs. The rain has stopped for now and the groundstaff is working on getting the covers off now. All on the call of the officials now! Hopefully, we get to see some action soon.

UPDATE 6.27 pm IST (12.57 pm GMT) - Nothing has changed in the last hour or so. The covers are completely on and the conditions are gloomy. It will take a lot for the ground staff when the rain clears to get the ground ready for play late in the day.
UPDATE 5.37 pm IST (12.07 pm GMT) - Oh, no! It has started raining again and the crowd has their umbrellas out. The covers are sadly coming back on.
UPDATE 5.14 pm IST (11.44 am GMT) - There is yet another update from the ground. If we do not have any more rain, then there will be an inspection at 6 pm IST (12.30 pm GMT). Fingers crossed.

UPDATE 5.03 pm IST (11.33 am GMT) - Early lunch has been taken and there is some good news as well. The conditions look a bit brighter and the RAIN HAS STOPPED for the time being. The ground staff are on their toes and working their magic but given the English weather, you never know when it might start raining again. For now, we hope that it remains bright and play can begin at the earliest after the interval. Stay tuned.

UPDATE 4.34 pm IST (11.04 am GMT) - Still no good news from the ground as the rain is sticking around. We are in for what looks to be a long wait. It has now been confirmed that EARLY LUNCH will be taken at 5 pm IST (11.30 am GMT). Also, there is some latest cricketing news but from the other side of the world where Australia have bundled New Zealand for 82 runs (who needed 196 runs for victory) to seal the three-game ODI series 2-0.

UPDATE 3.59 pm IST (10.29 am GMT) - The rain Gods are back and it looks like we're in for a longer wait. Thankfully, the ground staff had the pitch under covers before it started pouring down. We'll be back with the latest updates, stick around.

UPDATE 3.53 pm IST (10.23 am GMT) - Well, it has gone a lot darker in the last few minutes and the ground staff aren't taking any chances. The covers are being brought on and the pitch is being covered. Hopefully, this isn't a big delay and we can get started with the game. Stick around for more updates.

Dean Elgar, the captain of South Africa says that it looks like a good surface but it will be difficult for batting early on. Adds that they didn't do well in the previous Test but it is still 1-1 which is a positive thing. Informs that they have made four changes to the Playing XI.

English skipper, Ben Stokes is in for a chat. He starts by saying they will bowl first. Adds that they have done well bowling first this summer. Says the pitch has been under covers for a while and hopes that they can make the most of the conditions on offer.

South Africa (Playing XI) - Dean Elgar (C), Sarel Erwee, Keegan Petersen, Ryan Rickelton (In for Aiden Markram), Khaya Zondo (In for Rassie van der Dussen), Kyle Verreynne (WK), Wiaan Mulder (In for Simon Harmer), Marco Jansen (In for Lungi Ngidi), Keshav Maharaj, Kagiso Rabada and Anrich Nortje.
England (Playing XI) - Alex Lees, Zak Crawley, Ollie Pope, Joe Root, Harry Brook (In for Jonny Bairstow), Ben Stokes (C), Ben Foakes (WK), Stuart Broad, Ollie Robinson, Jack Leach and James Anderson.
TOSS - Up goes the coin and it lands in England's favor. They have elected to BOWL first.

We are back! The umpires and the players are back out in the middle. The South African opening pair of Dean Elgar and Sarel Erwee are ready to get their innings underway. James Anderson has the red cherry in hand and is raring to go. Let's play...
... THIRD INNINGS ...

Right then, as we expected, the bowlers continue to dominate proceedings in this game and another innings has flown by. England lead South Africa by 40 runs and the visitors will come out to bat whilst the conditions are still bowling friendly. It will be interesting to see the approach of their openers against the English pacers. Join us in a bit for South Africa's second innings.

England were a bit under the pump coming into this morning but they could add just 4 runs. Ben Foakes looked to rotate strike early on and Ollie Robinson was sent back on the second ball of the day. Leach soon followed and even Foakes couldn't hold on. England lost 3 wickets in just 16 deliveries bowled this morning and will now have to come out all guns blazing with the ball. Ollie Pope was the star for them with the bat as he scored a half-century but apart from that, there wasn't much to talk about. They do have a slender lead though and will look to make the most of it.

A superb start to the morning for the South African pacers and Kagiso Rabada and Marco Jansen have made short work of the English tail. The Proteas came back into the game late on Day 3 and have continued that momentum to keep the English lead down to just 40 runs. Jansen deservedly so picked up a five-wicket haul as Rabada took his wickets tally to four and this effort has now given the visitors renewed hope in this game.

OUT! CAUGHT AT SLIPS! Marco Jansen records his maiden fi-fer in Test cricket. An excellent start for South Africa this morning. It is a length ball, on off, shaping away a touch. Ben Foakes looks to defend it out but gets a thick outside edge. The ball flies to the left of third slip. Keegan Petersen gets low to his left and pouches it safely with both hands. England have been bundled out for 158 runs.
Commentary.Howout: c Keegan Petersen b Marco Jansen

Commentary.Commentary: Full length, outside off. Foakes leans in and drives it to mid off.
A low full toss, on off, Anderson pushes it gently back to the bowler.
This one drifts down the leg side, with some extra bounce. Anderson looks to clip it away but misses.

OUT! DRAGGED ON! Kagiso Rabada comes 'round the wicket now and it does the trick. Jack Leach walks back on a 3-ball duck. It is a good-length ball, outside off. Jack Leach hangs back and looks to cut it away. The ball takes the inside edge and shatters the stumps. South Africa are right back in the game. Kagiso Rabada gets his fourth wicket now. He has been sensational this morning.
Commentary.Howout: b Kagiso Rabada

Commentary.Commentary: James Anderson is the last man in for England.
This is angled into the pads, on a length, Foakes flicks it to deep square leg for one. The umpire signals a no ball as the bowler oversteps.
This is outside off and left alone yet again by Foakes.
Two dots in a row! Another one outside off, with some extra bounce off the deck. Ben Foakes lets it be.
Rabada goes full now, outside off. Foakes has no shot to offer.
And the second one as well! Just a single off the over then. It is on a good length, outside off. Leach looks to defend it away from his body but misses it completely.
Leach survives the first delivery! One more to go. It is a length ball, outside off. Leach shuffles across and leaves it alone for the keeper.
A length ball, on middle and leg, Foakes flicks it to mid-wicket and crosses for one. Jack Leach the new man on strike now.
Fuller, outside off, defended out.
A loud appeal for caught behind but the umpire shows no interest. It is a length ball, around off, nipping in off the deck. It brushes him on his thigh pads before going to the keeper.
Jansen serves it full, wide outside off. Foakes strokes it to deep point but decides against the single on the very first delivery of the over.
Jack Leach is the next man in. Also, Marco Jansen is set to bowl from the opposite end.

OUT! CAUGHT! Ollie Robinson faces his first delivery in the morning and has to trudge back. Just the start South Africa were after. Kagiso Rabada picks up his third wicket of the innings. It is a full-length ball, on off. Ollie Robinson just chips it to short extra cover. Dean Elgar stationed there takes a dolly.
Commentary.Howout: c Dean Elgar b Kagiso Rabada

Commentary.Commentary: It is full, wide of off. Ben Foakes reaches out and drives it through point for a single. First run for England straightaway.

We are ready for play on Day 4! The umpires and players are out in the middle and the English pair of Ben Foakes and Ollie Robinson are set to resume their stay at the crease. Kagiso Rabada has the ball in hand and he will finish off his incomplete over here. Let's play...

All is not lost for South Africa yet but they will need to be on top of their game early on Day 4 and look to keep the English lead to a minimum. Even after that, everything will depend on how their inexperienced batting line-up performs under pressure. A lot to play for and we might just come to know which way this game will eventually go on Day 4 itself. Stick around as we are not far away from the start of the morning session.

Day 3 is known as the moving day of a Test match but given it was the first day of this Test match, it still moved at a brisk pace. A lot of wickets fell, as many as 17 in fact and England ended the day with a small first innings lead. With 7 wickets down, they will look to add as many runs as possible to their 36-run lead and hope that their pacers do the job once again for them.

Hello and a warm welcome to Day 4 of the third and final Test between England and South Africa at the Oval in London. Day 3 was the first day on which we had play and with a bit of rain around and bad light stopping play early, about 70 overs were bowled throughout the day which is far less than the allotted 98 overs. There are still a couple of days left in the game and hopefully, we get to witness cricketing action without much interference.
... DAY 4, SESSION 1 ...

Right then, the Test match is nicely poised after an enthralling Day 3. England do have their noses in front but South Africa have a real shot at redeeming themselves here. The morning session on Day 4 could prove to be really vital. The first session on Day 4 will begin at 3.30 pm IST (10 am GMT) but you can join us in advance for the build-up. Cheers!

England started the day with the ball in hand and Ollie Robinson led from the front with a five-wicket haul to help his side restrict the Proteas to a modest total of 118. Having lost both their openers early, the hosts still had a positive start and then Joe Root and Ollie Pope put on a decent stand. Pope just kept on playing his shots but slowly, he kept running out of partners. Pope finally got out for 67 himself, exposing the tail and now the hosts are in danger of getting bundled out for a total of well under 200 runs.

South Africa might not have had much joy throughout the course of the day but the final session did belong to them. Marco Jansen kept on his impressive work as he added to his wickets tally and then Anrich Nortje got into the act as well. Kagiso Rabada kept on getting a bit of a stick but did pick up a couple of wickets towards the later half of the final session and those strikes have made a big difference. The visitors will now believe that if they get rid of the English tail and keep the lead to around 50 runs, they will be well and truly in this contest.

It is now official, Stumps have been called on Day 3! No play on the first two days of the deciding Test and finally, we get things started directly on Day 3. And, what a day it has been! In total, 17 wickets have fallen in the day with the Proteas getting bundled out and then England managing to avoid the same fate thanks to bad light. England do lead by 36 runs and have a slight edge in the game but a lot will depend on how things pan out early on day 4.

Well, whats happened here? The umpires have a little chat and they are signaling the players to come off. They take a reading that will serve as the benchmark and that is likely the end of play on Day 3. The day isn't over yet and the players can be called back on if the light improves but that seems a bit far-fetched. Stay tuned for further updates.
It is a length ball, around off. Ben Foakes waits for it and dabs it towards fourth slip. It falls short of the man there.
Fuller in length, on off. Ollie Robinson drives it down the ground to long on. The batters take three before the fielder cuts it out.
Outside off, Robinson looks to chase it but misses.

Drinks break! Well, England seemed to be cruising to a big first innings lead when they came back on after the Tea interval. This hasn't been the case though as the South African pacers have made a roaring comeback. Marco Jansen has been excellent and Anrich Nortje and Kagiso Rabada have been amongst the wickets as well. England's lead currently stands at 33 runs with 3 wickets left in the bag. It could get really interesting. With that said, Ollie Robinson walks out to bat.

OUT! CAUGHT BEHIND! Soft dismissal for Stuart Broad. That was short, and onto the body by Kagiso Rabada. Stuart Broad tries to make room and pull that one but he gets a bottom edge and the ball goes straight to Kyle Verreynne. South Africa are back in the game now.
Commentary.Howout: c Kyle Verreynne b Kagiso Rabada

Commentary.Commentary: Length ball, outside off, Foakes looks to chase it but gets beaten for pace this time. England now lead by 33 runs after 33 overs.
Much fuller, outside off. Foakes leans in and drives it to mid off.
A length ball, angled into the right-hander. Foakes gets an inside edge onto his pads.
Anrich Nortje comes 'round the wicket and serves it full, around off. Broad makes a bit room and slashes it through covers. They take one.
This is flicked to square leg for one.

It is a length ball, outside off. This one nips in off the deck. Ben Foakes tries to block it out but does so off the bottom half into the deck. He sees the ball landing besides the leg pole, to be more safe, he ends up kicking it towards fine leg.
FOUR! Stuart Broad smashes it over mid-off. That was full into the arc, Broad goes hard at the ball and clears the fielder of mid-off for a boundary.
Short pitched, around middle. Ben Foakes pulls it towards fine leg for a single
JAFFA! On a good length, close to the off pole, the ball pitches and just shapes away beautifully. Ben Foakes looks to play at it but is beaten all ends up.
On a good length, on off. Stuart Broad looks to loft this over the infield on off but misses it and a miss by the keeper as well and a bye is being taken.
Fuller length, around off. Stuart Broad tries to go big but didn't time it and the ball goes towards mid-on fielder.
On a good length, around off. Ben Foakes works it towards the third man for a single.
A length ball, around off. Broad stays back and smacks it to the man at mid off. Two dots in a row to end the over.
Play and a miss! Good length, on top of off. Broad looks to heave it away but misses.
This is full, angled into the pads. Foakes flicks it to deep square leg and crosses.
FOUR! Nortje errs in his line this time. It is a length ball, sliding down leg. Foakes hangs back and tickles it down to fine leg for four.
Back of a length, outside off, nips in off the deck. Foakes stays back, gets on top of the bounce and punches it to covers. Not in the gap though.
A length ball, on off stump. Foakes tucks it to the leg side.
Fuller length, outside off. Ben Foakes pushes it towards cover for a quick single a shy at the nonstriker end but he was home easily.
On a good length, outside off. Ben Foakes lets that one go through to the keeper.
On a good length, around off. Ben Foakes defends solidly off the front foot.
Short of length, outside off. Ben Foakes tries to block that one but misses it.
Fuller length, around off. Stuart Broad drives off the front foot for an easy single.
On a good length, outside off. Stuart Broad tries to go big but misses it completely.
Pitches it up now, at 147 clicks and in that channel around off. Ben Foakes makes a watchful leave.
On the pads, Foakes flicks it away past backward square leg and picks up a couple of runs.
Length again, attacking the stumps, Foakes keeps it out.
Good length, around off and just shaping in a touch. Foakes gets beaten on the inside edge as he looks to defend it out.
Fuller in length and outside off, Ben Foakes edges it down with soft hands towards fourth slip where the fielder makes a good stop.
A length ball, well outside off, Foakes doesn't play at it.
Fuller length, around off. Stuart Broad plays it back to the bowler.
Back of a length, around off. Stuart Broad defends it off the front foot.
Stuart Broad comes in at number 8.

OUT! CAUGHT BEHIND! First wicket for Kagiso Rabada and that to of the big fish, Ollie Pope. Back of the length, angling away from Ollie Pope, outside off. Pope tries to punch it away but gets an outside edge. It carries to Kyle Verreynne behind the sticks who makes no mistake. There is surely a comeback on the cards now for the Proteas.
Commentary.Howout: c Kyle Verreynne b Kagiso Rabada

Commentary.Commentary: On a good length, around off. Ollie Pope blocks it off the front foot.
FOUR! Fuller length, onto the pads. Ollie Pope flicks it towards the fine leg for a boundary.
On a good length, around off. Ollie Pope blocks it off the front foot.
Pitched up, around off, Ben Foakes defends it out.
Ben Foakes is the new man in now.

OUT! CAUGHT! Ben Stokes is a goner this time around and Anrich Nortje has his man. This is served on a fuller length and angled in from around off. The ball holds its line as Stokes looks to just hit through the line. The outside edge is found and the ball goes straight into the pouches of Sarel Erwee at first slip. Erwee makes no mistake and the English skipper departs after an edgy inning. England lead by 11, can South Africa seize the opportunity?
Commentary.Howout: c Sarel Erwee b Anrich Nortje

Commentary.Commentary: Leg bye! On the pads, Ollie Pope looks to tickle it fine but it comes off the pads and down to fine leg. They pick up a leg bye.
Back of a length, around off and this is tapped towards point.

In the air...dropped! Length ball, around off, Ben Stokes gets a bit low and looks to launch it over long off. The bat turns in his hands and the ball comes off the toe end as well. The ball goes a long way up and over mid off. Dean Elgar runs back over his left shoulder and puts in the dive but he can't reach it. Stokes survives and he picks up a single as well.
Anrich Nortje starts from around the wicket and serves a very full delivery around the off stump. Ben Stokes manages to get some bat on it.
Change. Anrich Nortje comes into the attack now.

FOUR! Fuller length, angling in. Ollie Pope flicks from his front foot nicely into the gap through wide mid-on Keshav Maharaj chases and tries to stop the ball but the third umpire signals it a boundary.
On a good length, outside off. Ollie Pope on the backfoot plays it late and ends up chopping it near his feet.
Back of a length, angling in. Ollie Pope plays it towards a vacant short leg.
Fuller length, around off. Ollie Pope pushes it off the front foot towards the bowler.
FOUR! Luck running England's way. That was short, around off. Ollie Pope tries to defend it but the ball takes the outside edge goes over the slip cordon for a boundary.
Fuller length, on the off pole. Ben Stokes tries to block this one but gets an inside edge and the ball goes towards the square leg.

Full and wide, Ollie Pope goes after it and drives it off the outer half of the bat past backward point. The fielder at deep point runs to his left and slides in to make a stop. Two taken and the scores are now level.
Fullish delivery, angled well across the right-hander, left alone by Pope.
Around the top of off, Ollie Pope makes a watchful leave.
Back of a length, close to the off pole. Pope looks to step out but misses the ball.

FOUR! Top edge but Ollie Pope gets away with it and brings up a very well-made FIFTY. Shorter again from Jansen, at the body, Pope looks to pull but gets a top edge that goes down into the vacant fine leg fence for a boundary.
Short of a length and over middle, Ollie Pope looks to pull but gets it off the gloves towards square leg. That must be a sore one for Pope.
Short of length, around off. Ben Stokes goes on the back foot and punches it through covers for a boundary and Ben Stokes gets off the mark in style.
Short of length, angling in. Ben Stokes makes room for himself but Kagiso Rabada follows him and Ben Stokes gets beaten by the pace through to the keeper.
Fuller length, on off. Ben Stokes blocks it towards the bowler.
On a good length, around off. Ben Stokes blocks solidly off the front foot.
Fuller length, angling in. Ollie Pope gets an inside edge onto the pads and the ball rolls past the man at first slip for a single.
Fuller length, onto off. Ollie Pope blocks it towards silly mid on.
Rabada to bowl from the other end.
Back to over the wicket now, full and on off. Ben Stokes defends it off the front foot.
Ben Stokes comes in at number 6.

OUT! CAUGHT! Harry Brook gets suckered into Marco Jansen's plan and he will be disappointed with that shot. Jansen sticks to around the wicket and delivers a shorter one around the hips. Brook shuffles a bit as he tries to pull it up and over the fence behind square on the leg side. Brook mistimes it and Kagiso Rabada from fine leg runs towards long leg and pouches it safely. Brook departs for a low score on debut and England still trail by 11 runs.
Commentary.Howout: c Kagiso Rabada b Marco Jansen

Commentary.Commentary: On a fullish length and outside off, Brook lets it through to the keeper.
Length again, around off, Brook defends it out.
Good length, from around the wicket and outside off. Brook leaves it alone.
Jansen starts off proceedings after the interval with a fuller delivery around off. Harry Brook flicks it away towards mid-wicket.
We are back. South Africa players take the field. Followed by Harry Brook and Ollie Pope who walk out with their swords. Marco Jansen to start with the ball.

UPDATE 9.46 pm IST (4.16 pm GMT) - Just as expected, the rain has passed by. The umpires are out on the field to have a look at the playing conditions as the covers are being taken off now. The match will resume at 10 pm IST (4.30 pm GMT) if the rain stays away.

Around the top of off, defended out by Pope.
Back of a length and at the body, Harry Brook hops and keeps it down towards square leg for one more.
Hard length, outside off, tapped away past the slip cordon for a single.
Full and around off, this is driven through the mid off region. Dean Elgar chases it down as the batters come back for the third with ease.

Looks like it has started to drizzle, as we see raincoats coming out in the crowd with a few umbrellas opening up as well. The radar says that it is just a passing shower. The umpires allow the play to continue for now.
Back of a length and outside off, Pope taps it off the back foot and towards deep point for a single. Also, a no ball is called for overstepping.
Good length again and outside off, Pope looks to steer it past the slip cordon but Marco Jansen at fourth slip makes a sharp stop.
Good length, at 148 clicks and around off. Ollie Pope solidly keeps it out.
On a good length, outside off. Harry Brook leaves that one alone.
On a good length, around middle and leg. Harry Brook blocks it off the front foot towards the bowler.
On a good length, outside off. Harry Brook lets that one go through to the keeper.
Short of length, around middle. Harry Brook pulls it towards short mid-wicket.
Fuller length, outside off. Harry Brook lets that ball go through to the keeper.
Fuller length, onto the pads. Ollie Pope works it towards fine leg. 100 up for England.
Full and straight, pushed towards mid on.

Oh, is that a missed opportunity? It looks like it. Short and wide, Ollie Pope looks for the upper cut but mistimes it. Ryan Rickelton at deep point doesn't pick it up and stays put. The ball goes on the bounce towards him and maybe, if he did pick it up, it would have been a chance. Just the single then.
Full and angling down leg, Ollie Pope looks to flick it away but misses and gets hit on the pads.
Length ball, around off, Pope looks to play at it but gets an inside edge onto the pads.
Pitched up this time, around off and at 147 clicks. This is driven on the up and through extra cover for a couple of runs.
Hits the length hard and bowls it outside off, Pope waits for it and guides it on the bounce towards the slip cordon.
FOUR! Jansen serves a half-volley outside off and Harry Brook latches onto it. This is driven squarer and on the up, through cover-point for yet another boundary.
Fullish length, angled across the right-hander. Harry Brook shoulders arms.
FOUR! Harry Brook is off the mark in Test cricket with a boundary. Full and wide, Brook goes back and across to cream it through covers for a boundary. Brook will be a relieved man now.
Jansen pulls back the length and offers width, Harry Brook looks to thrash it away but mistimes it badly towards mid off.
On a fuller length and on off stump as well, Brook defends it under his eye line.
Serves it full and around off, Brook drives it towards extra cover.
Full and straight, at 145 clicks and Ollie Pope flicks it straight to the man at square leg.
FOUR! Clipped nicely! Length again, on the pads, Ollie Pope whips it away through square leg for a boundary.
Length again, around middlde and worked away towards wide mid on.
Good-length ball, at 146 clicks and angling into middle, Pope hops and keeps it out on the leg side.
Edged but doesn't carry! Good length, close to the off pole and Ollie Pope plays at it with soft hands. The ball takes the outside edge but lands well in front of the man at first slip.
Nortje starts off with a length ball, outside off and this is left alone by Ollie Pope.
It will be Anrich Nortje to steam in from the other end.
Jansen starts off with a wicket-maiden! Pitched up on off stump, Harry Brook makes a solid block off the front foot.
Harry Brook is the new man in for England. He walks out on his Test debut. He will surely have some butterflies in his stomach as he strides towards the crease.

OUT! TAKEN! Keegan Petersen takes a blinder of a catch and Marco Jansen strikes right after the interval. Just a tad bit shorter and well outside off, Joe Root has a slash at it but doesn't quite control it. The ball flies off the toe-end and goes to the right of Petersen at third slip who pouches it out of thin air. Big wicket this for Jansen and South Africa as Root was looking positive out there.
Commentary.Howout: c Keegan Petersen b Marco Jansen

Commentary.Commentary: Full and around off, Root comes down the pitch and drives it towards silly mid on.
Goes fuller and brings the ball a bit closer to the off pole, Joe Root makes yet another easy leave.
Shorter in length and well outside off, left alone by Root.
Jansen starts off with a length ball, angling across the right-hander. Joe Root gets a stride out and pushes it out towards cover.

The final session is set to begin. A very crucial session for England as they head out with an aim to post a lead on the board. South Africa would need something special here to restrict England. South Africa players are seen to be in a huddle before they take the field. Followed by Joe Root and Ollie Pope who walk out to continue with the bat. Marco Jansen to start with the ball here.
... Day 3, Session 3 ...

South Africa could not apply the same pressure with the new ball as the opposition did. The sun was beating down the ground which made the batting conditions much favourable. England stuck to their plan and came all guns blazing. They lost their openers quite early than they would've envisioned but Ollie Pope and Joe Root were able to score runs at a brisk rate which has put them in the driving seat in this Test match. England would be aiming to put on some healthy lead before the end of Day's play. South Africa, on the other hand, would be aiming to take wickets at regular intervals which helps them to stay in the game. Do join us at 9 pm IST (3.30 pm GMT) to find out how things pan out in the final session on Day 3.

Yet another session that is dominated by England. First with the ball and then with the blade as well. The England batters walk into the Tea break with a deficit of 34 runs. The South African tail could not wag as much as they would've liked and were bundled out for just 118 runs, courtesy of some top bowling by Stuart Broad in the post-Lunch session.
Fuller length, outside off. Ollie Pope let that ball go through to the keeper. Tea on day 3
On a good length, outside off. Ollie Pope tries to go hard at the ball but misses it.
On a good length, outside off. Ollie Pope nearly chops it on.
Short, outside off. Ollie Pope works it towards slips.
Fuller length, outside off. Ollie Pope drives it towards covers.
On a good length, around off. Joe Root plays it towards point for a single.

FOUR! Length again, around middle and leg, this time Ollie Pope does manage to get inside the line and gets a fine tickle on it as well. The ball races away into the fine leg fence. England trail by just 35 now.
Good length, around the top of off, Pope punches it out towards extra cover.
Length ball, sliding onto middle and leg, Ollie Pope looks to shuffle across and whip it away. The ball goes off the inside edge and into the pads before rolling away onto the leg side.
Fuller in length once again and a fair bit outside off, Pope leaves it alone.
This is fuller and outside off, Ollie Pope shoulders arms at it.
Good hustle by the English batters. Back of a length, around off, Joe Root drops it down towards point and hurries through for the run.
Fuller length, outside off. Ollie Pope lets that ball go through to the keeper.
On a good length, angling in. Ollie Pope comes down the track but the ball hits his pads and an appeal from the bowler but the umpire doesn't seem interested.
Short, outside off. Ollie Pope opens that bat face and works it towards the slips.
Short of length, outside off. Ollie Pope plays it towards deep point for no run.
FOUR! Poor delivery by Anrich Nortje. That was short, wide outside off. Ollie Pope slaps it through extra cover for a boundary.
Short of length, outside off. Ollie Pope lets that ball go through to the keeper.
FOUR! A poor way to end the over by Wiaan Mulder. This is a half-volley on the pads, Root clips it away through mid-wicket and picks up a boundary.
Goes a bit fuller now and serves it in that channel around off, Joe Root lets it through to the keeper.
Good length, on middle and leg, nudged away towards short mid-wicket.
Keeps it on the shorter side and bowls it over middle now. Root hops onto the back foot and keeps it out on the off side.
Banged in short and outside off, this is pulled away off the toe end of the bat towards deep mid-wicket for a couple of runs.
Mulder starts off with a shortish delivery outside off. The ball nips away off the deck as Root looks to come down the track and play at it.
Change. Wiaan Mulder comes into the attack now.
On a good length, around off. Ollie Pope knocks it back to the bowler.
Fuller length, outside off. Joe Root drives it to the fielder at covers but they scramble through for a single.
FOUR! That was short, outside off. Joe Root punches it through extra cover for a boundary.
Short of length, around the middle stump. Joe Root nearly chopped that on but that ball hits his shoes and rolls towards slips.
Short of length, onto the leg stump. Joe Root tucks it towards the short leg.
On a good length, outside off. Joe Root lets that ball go through to the keeper.

FOUR! It's going from bad to worse here for Kagiso Rabada. Serves it full and straight, Ollie Pope drives it gloriously down the ground for a boundary. Rabada has now gone for 49 runs in just 6 overs.
NO BALL! Length, outside off and it is left alone but Rabada has overstepped yet again and a no ball is called.
Goes a bit fuller and around off, Pope looks to step out yet again but this time he is beaten past the outside edge.

FOUR! Edged away and nothing is going Rabada's way at the moment. Length ball, around off, Ollie Pope steps out and looks to go across the line. The ball goes off the outside edge and past backward point as well for a boundary.
On a fullish length, angling it into the leg stump, Pope flicks it towards square leg.
Too full and too straight from Kagiso Rabada, Root flicks it away through mid-wicket and races back for the third.

Around the top of off, Root goes on the front foot and pushes it past the diving fielder at backward point for a brace. Another no ball has been called for overstepping and Rabada is getting more and more frustrated out there.
FOUR! Muscled! Just a fraction short and around off, Joe Root picks up the length early and pulls it well in front of mid-wicket for a boundary.
Good length, outside off, angling across. Pope leaves it alone for the keeper. A successful over from Jansen comes to an end.
Joe Root gets off the mark here. It is full, drifting down leg. Root flicks it to deep square leg and takes a single.
Good movement yet again! It is a length ball, around middle, shaping in off the deck. Root is caught inside his crease and gets pinged on his thigh pads.
Full length, outside off. Root dances down the track and pushes it gently towards covers.
Outside off, left alone.
Joe Root walks in next.

OUT! LBW! Marco Jansen breaks this stand which was starting to hurt them. It looks plumb to the naked eye. Zak Crawley has a chat with his partner and goes for the review. Coming to the delivery, it is a length ball that lands around off and nips in off the deck. Zak Crawley looks to push it down the track but misses it. The ball goes through to ping his pads. Marco Jansen appeals an the umpire raises his finger in a flash. Later the review also does not help Zak Crawley as the Ball Tracking confirms three reds.
Commentary.Howout: lbw b Marco Jansen

Commentary.Commentary: A length ball, on top of off. Pope gets it to backward point off the outer half.
It is full again, wide of off. Pope leans in and drives it towards point. Kagiso Rabada has to reload his final delivery as he oversteps yet again.
Fuller in length, outside off, it shapes in late off the deck. Pope leaves it alone.

FOUR! Ollie Pope is on fire here. He has been quick off the pull so far. It is a short ball, on off. Pope picks up the length quite early and pulls it through square leg for a boundary. The umpire signals a no ball now as the bowler oversteps. England right on top at the moment.
A length ball, around off. Pope gets it past gully off the outer half. Two taken this time.
Rabada dishes it full, on off. This is the perfect length that he would be aiming for. Pope drives it to covers on the front foot.
Ollie Pope uses his feet this time and blocks it to the off side.
Rabada drags his length back this time, in the channel. Pope stays back and looks to have a poke at it but gets beaten this time.
Three dots in a row to end the over! Full length, wide of off. Crawley looks to go for the booming drive but gets beaten on the inside edge this time.
Much fuller, on off, this is straightens a bit after hitting the deck. Zak Crawley reads it really well and leaves it alone for the keeper.
Good length, angled across the right-hander, in the channel. Crawley lets it be.
It is touch fuller, on off. Pope comes down the track and drives it past mid on. The batters take three before the fielder cuts it out.
FOUR! Easy pickings for Ollie Pope. It is a length ball, on the pads, much straighter. Pope hangs back and glances it down to fine leg for a boundary.
Outside off, left alone.
Another one that nips away. A length ball, wide of off, moves away a hint off the deck. Zak Crawley looks to chase it but misses.
JAFFA! A full-length ball, outside off. Zak Crawley looks to defend it out but gets beaten past the outside edge as this one nips away.

A huge appeal for lbw but turned down. Rabada serves it on a length, outside off. Zak Crawley thinks it will be much straighter and offers no shot at it. Although, it hits the rough patch and nips is a touch off the deck. Zak Crawley is rappes on his back pad. Kagiso Rabada appeals but the umpire denies. South Africa take a review. The UltraEdge confirms no bat is involved. The Ball Tracking shows that the ball is missing the wickets. South Africa lose a review here.
On a length, wide of off. Zak Crawley lets it through to the keeper. A great start to the over by Rabada.
Fraction short, outside off, nipping in a touch. Crawley has no shot to offer.
Length ball, on top of off. Crawley blocks it back to the bowler.
Fuller, straying on the pads this time. Crawley flicks it to mid-wicket for a single.
This is on a good length, lands outside off and shapes in off the deck. Zak Crawley shoulders his arms at it. The ball sails over the stumps and into the keeper's mitts.
A length ball, on off. Crawley blocks it out watchfully.
Jansen getting some swing here. This one lands around middle and shapes in. Zak Crawley gets rapped on his pads. Going down leg.
NO BALL! It is full, around middle, nips into the batter off the deck. Crawley misses his flick. It goes to the leg side off his pads. The umpire signals a no ball as the bowler oversteps.
This is outside off, angled across. Crawley shoulders his arms at it.
It is a full-length ball, angled across the right-hander, in the channel. Zak Crawley walks down the track and looks to defend it out but misses.
FOUR! This time in front of square! Short of a length and around off, Pope pulls it past the man at wide mid on and the ball just about beats that same man to the ropes.
FOUR! Banged in short this time, around off, Ollie Pope is quick to latch onto it and plays a well-controlled pull shot through mid-wicket for a boundary.
Lovely bowling! Rabada serves it a bit fuller and angles it in from around off. The ball straightens sharply off the deck and zips past the outside edge.
Good carry from Rabada! Pitched up, around off and this is left alone by Pope.
On a hard length this time, around off and Pope defends it back onto the deck.
Good length, close to the off pole, straightening off the deck. Ollie Pope plays inside the line of the ball.
On a good length, onto the leg stump. Zak Crawley looks to hit this towards square leg but misses it.
Fuller delivery, around middle. Zak Crawley pushes it towards short mid-wicket.
On a good length, outside off. Zak Crawley looks to poke it but in the end leaves this one alone.
On a good length, wide of off. Zak Crawley lets that ball go through to the keeper.
On a good length, around off. Ollie Pope pushes it towards the point for a quick single.
Ollie Pope comes in at number 3.

Lees looks for the straight drive with hard hands but the ball nips in off the deck and goes between bat and pad to hit the top of middle stump. Lees departs after a fast start and South Africa will now look to build up on this.
