Commentary.Commentary: Full and outside off, Crawley lets it through to the keeper.
Around the top of off, at 142 clicks and nipping back in off the deck. Crawley manages to keep it out on the leg side.
Length ball, in that channel around off, Zak Crawley leaves it alone.
Pitched up, on off stump and solidly blocked off by Crawley.

Nicely timed yet again. Length, on middle and leg, Lees flicks it well in front of square on the leg side and the ball seems to be running away. The sluggish outfield slows it down and it will only be a three.
FOUR! Not the best of opening spells by Rabada here. Length ball, around off, Alex Lees goes after it and gets it off the middle of the bat, through cover-point and picks up a boundary.
On a good length, outside off. Zak Crawley lets that one go through to the keeper.
Great leave! That was short, around the middle. Zak Crawley lets that ball go over the stumps by trusting the bounce this time.
Fuller length, onto middle stump. Zak Crawley blocks it off the front foot.
On a good length, outside off. Zak Crawley lets that ball go through to the keeper.
Short of length, around off. Alex Lees tucks it towards cover for a quick single.
Fuller length, angling in. Alex Lees plays it towards deep square leg for a single.
It will be Marco Jansen to steam in from the other end.

Clearly off the deck! Very full and around off, Zak Crawley looks to jam it out on the off side but the ball goes u[ppishly and towards point. The fielder over there takes a low catch and appeals. It is sent upstairs and the replays show that the ball was dabbed onto the deck by Crawley before it went to the fielder. End of an exciting first over by Kagiso Rabada and England are off to a positive start.

Pitched up, in that channel around off and not much movement on offer. Crawley lets it through to the keeper.
Rabada goes very full and on off stump, Crawley does well to dig it out.
On a fullish length and outside off, Zak Crawley makes a watchful leave first up.

Alex Lees and England are away! Kagiso Rabada starts off with a fullish delivery on the pads, a bit of a freebie and Lees just plays it in front of mid-wicket. The ball slows down and the fielder from mid-wicket is able to hunt it down. Three taken.
We are back! The umpires and the players are back on the field. Zak Crawley and Alex Lees are the openers for England. Kagiso Rabada has the new ball in hand and is raring to go.
... FOURTH INNINGS ...

England were in trouble in the opening session on Day 4 as their tailenders were bundled out cheaply and their pacers couldn't take early wickets either. But they have made a roaring comeback here and have done brilliantly to keep the Proteas lead down to just 129 runs. The skipper, Ben Stokes led from the front and picked up 3 wickets, so did Stuart Broad. James Anderson and Ollie Robinson too chipped in with a couple of wickets and now England is in pole position to seal this series. Join us in a bit for the run chase.

South Africa were brilliant with the ball early on Day 4 and then Dean Elgar and Sarel Erwee did well to see off the new ball and put on a 58-run opening stand. Erwee fell and then Elgar misses out on a review where he was Not Out and that cost them dearly. The middle order provided little to no resistance and the inexperience has shown here. South Africa will now look to come out all guns blazing with the ball and try to get early wickets in order to make a match of it.

That's it then, South Africa after a very good opening stand have been bundled out for 169 runs! The target for England is simple, 130 runs to win and seal the series 2-1! It has been yet another engrossing day of Test cricket so far. Captivating from start to finish but England are in the driver's seat now and they will fancy their chances of winning the game.

OUT! CAUGHT AND BOWLED! James Anderson takes his second wicket. It is a short ball, on off. Kyle Verreynne stands tall and throws his blade at it. The ball takes the outside edge and lobs towards short mid on. James Anderson goes to his right and takes a dolly. South Africa have been bundled out for 169 runs here.

Broad goes short, outside off. Kyle Verreynne looks to cut it away but gets beaten by pace here.
Around the top of off, edged away down to third man for a couple of runs.
Around off, pushed away towards the cover region.
Fullish delivery, angling in from outside off and leaving the batter. Keshav Maharaj plays inside the line of the ball.
Fuller and well outside off, left alone.
Shorter and around the hips, tucked away towards short fine leg for one more.
Around the top of off, this is pulled away down to fine leg for a single.
Length again, on the pads, worked away towards mid-wicket.
Length ball, on middle, Verreynne looks to work it leg side but gets a leading edge towards cover-point.
Beaten! Nagging length, close to the off pole and Verreynne looks to drive at it. The ball whizzes past the outside edge.
Around the hips, Keshav Maharaj tucks it away fine and the batters race back for the third with ease.
Fullish delivery, outside off, Keshav Maharaj looks to have a poke at it but pulls out at the last moment.
Broad starts the new spell with a good-length ball outside off. Verreynne taps it in front of cover and picks up a single.
Fuller and angling into middle, Maharaj blocks it out.
Length ball, angling down the leg side, Maharaj leaves it alone.
Very full, a low full toss and outside off, this is played off the inner half of the bat through mid-wicket for a couple of runs.
Stokes spills it down leg yet again, Far enough for Maharaj though. Ben Foakes dives low to his left to make a sharp stop.
FOUR! Bonus runs for South Africa. It is a short ball, sliding down leg. Maharaj glances it down to fine leg for four. The lead moves to 118 runs now.

Good length, on the stumps and solidly defended out by Verreynne.
Anderson angles this one into middle stump and the ball straightens after pitching, Verreynne does well to block it.
Shorter and over leg stump, Keshav Maharaj pulls it behind square on the leg side for a run.
This is pitched up around off, Keshav Maharaj eases it towards cover.
Fuller and on off stump, Maharaj manages to keep it out on the off side.
Length ball, in that channel around off and nipping away. Keshav Maharaj gets beaten past the outside edge.
Good length, over off, Verreynne defends it back onto the deck.
Around the top of off, nipping away, Verreynne plays it with soft hands and towards backward point.
Leg bye! Fuller and sliding onto the pads, Keshav Maharaj looks to flick but misses. The ball goes off the pads towards short fine leg and they get a leg bye.
Nagging length, around off and nipping away, Maharaj plays inside the line of the ball.
FOUR! Driven and into the gap. Full and wide, Keshav Maharaj drives it through the vacant wide mid off region for a much-needed boundary.
Good length, around the top of off, Keshav Maharaj gets behind the line of the ball to block.
Length, close to the off stump, kept out by Verreynne.
Around the top of off, Kyle Verreynne solidly keeps it out.
Around off, stroked away towards cover for a single.

Fuller and around off, Kyle Verreynne opens the face of the bat and drives it behind point for a single.
On a length and angling into middle, Kyle Verreynne blocks it out off the front foot.
Keshav Maharaj is the new batter in. Also, it will be James Anderson to steam in from the other end.

OUT! CAUGHT! Ben Stokes with the double strike and South Africa lose their eighth wicket now. This is full, from around the wicket and angling in from around off. Kagiso Rabada sticks out his bat as he looks to defend but the outside edge is found. Harry Brook at second slip moves to his right and pouches it safely. The umpires go upstairs to check for a bump catch but it is clearly off the edge and the English skipper has done the trick for his team yeat again. South Africa in serious trouble now.

Commentary.Commentary: Is it out? The umpire takes it upstairs to confirm. The soft signal is OUT! The replays later confirm that it is not a bump ball and the big screen shows out.

We are back for the final session. England players take the field. Followed by Kyle Verreynne and Kagiso Rabada, the new batter who walk in for South Africa. It will be Ben Stokes to complete his over.
... Day 4, Session 3 ...

A session that truly belonged to England. They have managed to get the ball moving in the post-Lunch session and that derailed the South African innings. It was Stuart Broad and James Anderson who worked in tandem in the first half of the Lunch session. They picked up three wickets in total to get rid of the top order, who seemed settled at the crease. Then Ollie Robinson came into the attack and took two wickets in quick succession to put his side back on top. Later, it was a limping Ben Stokes, who led his side from the front and took a wicket at the brink of Tea to make it worse for the opposition. For South Africa, their inexperienced batting lineup might cost them this game yet again. After Dean Elgar slipped out, no other batter stood it and it was a mini-collapse for the Proteas. They need their tail to wag in the final session here and delay the chase for England as much as they could. The lead currently stands at 106 runs. To find out how things pan out, do join us at 9 pm IST (3.30 pm GMT).

OUT! TIMBER! A gem of a delivery from Ben Stokes and Marco Jansen is beaten all ends up. This is full and around off, nipping in a long way off the deck. Jansen just looks to defend it off the front foot but leaves a huge gap between bat and pad. The ball goes between that gap and knocks over the leg stump. England have the breakthrough they needed and that will be Tea on Day 4.
Commentary.Howout: b Ben Stokes

Commentary.Commentary: Stokes pitches it up, full and outside off, Jansen offers no shot to it.
Shorter and around the hips, nudged away towards short mid-wicket.
Shorter and way down the leg side, Ben Foakes collects it well.
Fullish length, on the fifth stump line and it is left alone for the keeper to collect.
This is angled into middle and leg, Verreynne pushes it away towards mid on.
Around the top of off, tentatively pushed away towards mid off.
Length, around off, blocked out.

Good length, on off and jagging back in sharply. Kyle Verreynne looks to block but misses and gets pinged high on the pads. Verreynne is outside his crease and Ollie Pope shows some sharp work at fourth slip as he has a shy. The throw takes Verreynne by surprise and he falls over.

SIX! In the air and in the gap. A good short ball over middle and leg, Kyle Verreynne looks to take it on but gets a top edge. The ball flies down towards fine leg and hits the ropes on the full. A maximum is signalled.
BEATEN! Ben Stokes angles it in on a fullish length and into off stump. Marco Jansen looks to block but the ball straightens and beats the outside edge.
Length ball, in that channel around off, left alone by Jansen.
This is short and on leg stump, doesn't rise up much, Marco Jansen ducks under it well.
Stokes goes even fuller and bowls it around off, Jansen looks to push at it but gets beaten on the inside edge this time.
Good length, around the top of off, Marco Jansen plays inside the line of the ball.
Fuller length, outside off, left alone for the keeper to collect.

No ball and OUT! The English players rejoice but the catch won't count. Full and wide, shaping away. Marco Jansen looks to drive but gets a thick outside edge. Ollie Pope takes a good catch to his right at fourth slip but a no ball is called for overstepping. A huge let off this.
Fullish length, outside off, Kyle Verreynne makes yet another leave. Maiden!
Perfect line and length, around the top of off, Kyle Verreynne stays back and keeps it out on the off side.
Top delivery! Length ball, close to the off pole and just holding its line. Kyle Verreynne looks to get behind the line but the ball zips past the outside edge.
Full and outside off, Kyle Verreynne lets it through to the keeper.
This is pitched up, around off shaping in late, Kyle Verreynne makes an easy leave.
This one angles down leg. Kyle Verreynne misses his flick.
Length, in the channel, Jansen thinks to play at it first but does not go through with his shot here.
Fuller, on the pads, Kyle Verreynne flicks it to deep square leg for a single.
Touch fuller, outside off, shapes away again. Kyle Verreynne has no shot to offer.
A length ball, shaping away yet again. Kyle Verreynne leaves it alone.
Outside off, left alone.

It is a good-length ball, on middle and leg. Kyle Verreynne looks to heave it across the line but misses. It goes on to hit him in the box. Kyle Verreynne seems to be in some pain. The crowd groans as the replay is shown on the big screen here.

FOUR! Top shot! It is fuller, outside off. Marco Jansen creams it through covers for a boundary. No chance for Ben Stokes to chase it down as the outfield has gotten a bit quicker with the sun beating down.
It is pitched up, outside off. Jansen drives it back to the bowler. Ollie Robinson gets low and makes a half-stop.
A short ball, this time, on leg. Jansen ducks under it. The umpire signals a no ball.
Good length, outside off, shapes in off the deck a bit late. Jansen shoulders his arms at it.
Marco Jansen is the new man in.

OUT! LBW! Ollie Robinson gets another wicket here. Brilliant bowling by him. Zondo though takes the review for lbw. It is a length ball, that lands outside off and zips in off the deck. Zondo offers no shot this time and gets pinged on his thigh pads. Ollie Robinson appeals and the finger goes up. The Ball Tracking shows that it is umpire's call on hitting the wickets and Zondo has to head back to the pavilion.
Commentary.Howout: lbw b Ollie Robinson

Commentary.Commentary: Length ball, on off, Kyle Verreynne pushes it to point for one. He gets off the mark.

FOUR BYES! Runs are coming in thick and fast for the Proteas now. It is spilled down the leg side by Ollie Robinson. Kyle Verreynne misses his flick, it goes past the keeper and runs down to fine leg fence.

FOUR! Boundaries in quick succession for Zondo here. This is a very good-looking shot. It is fuller, on off. Zondo caresses it past mid off. The ball has enough legs to reach the boundary. The lead moves to 88. Still 50 overs left in the day.
Outside off, left alone.
This one is on a length, around off, it nips in off the deck. Zondo gets squared up this time.
FOUR! Up and over! Back of a length, outside off. Zondo stands tall and upper cuts it over backward point. It clears the fielder and races away.
A length ball, on the pads, at 130 clicks. Zondo blocks it out solidly. Ben Stokes is barely going though his follow through. He is limping here
Full length, outside off, shaping away. Zondo leaves it alone for the keeper.
Kyle Verreynne is the new man in. South Africa lead by 80 runs at the moment.

OUT! CHOPPED ON! Ollie Robinson picks up his 50th Test wicket. He has bowled brilliant thoughout and finally gets into the wicket's column here. It is a length ball, wide outside off. It hits the deck and nips in sharply off. Wiaan Mulder hangs back and looks to cut it away. It takes the inside edge and rattles the stumps. South Africa lose their fifth wicket now.
Commentary.Howout: b Ollie Robinson

Commentary.Commentary: Good length, outside off. Mulder hangs back and punches it through covers. The batters come back for the second run with ease.
Back of a length, outside off, shaping away. Mulder leaves it alone.
A length ball, on off, Mulder defends it to the off side.
Another length delivery, it lands outside off and nips in a touch. Mulder gets behind and defends it to covers.
Length ball, on off. Mulder defends it to the off side.
A length ball, angled into the pads, Zondo flicks it to mid-wicket.

Good length, outside off, it extracts some extra bounce off the deck. Zondo looks to chase it initially but thinks against it in the end. It looks like he might've nicked it when he tried to make a late leave. The slip cordon is happy especially Joe Root. He convinced Stokes to take the review for caught behind. The UltraEdge later confirms that Khaya Zondo gets no bat on it. England lose all their reviews now. How costly will it prove to be?
Back of a length, on off. Zondo gets on his toes and blocks it to the off side.
Length, on the pads, Mulder flicks it to deep square leg and crosses for one. The lead moves to 78.
FOUR! Easy pickings for Mulder! Full length, sliding down leg. Mulder hangs back and glances it down to fine leg for a boundary.
NO BALL! Length ball, around off. Zondo steers it to third man for a single. The umpire signals a no ball due to overstepping.
This one comes back into the pads. Zondo gets pinged high on his pads.
On the pads, nudged to the leg side.
On a fuller length, outside off. moving away a touch. Mulder lets it go.
Full length, outside off. Mulder steps out and works it back to the bowler. Ollie Robinson gets low, gathers the ball and has a shy at the striker's end. It goes past the stumps though.
It is outside off, Mulder leaves it alone for the keeper.
On off, blocked out.
Full length, on off. It gets some extra bounce off the deck. The ball gets big on Mulder. It goes off the outer half towards gully. Falls short though.
Mulder looks to flick it away but misses. It goes to square leg off his pads. They collect a leg bye.
Length, on off, blocked out.
FOUR! Nicely played! A short ball, on middle and leg. Mulder swivels on his back foot and pulls it behind square on the leg side to find a boundary.
Length ball, on the pads, Mulder flicks it to mid-wicket.
Good length, on fourth stump, shaping away. Mulder shoulders his arms at it.
This one holds its line, outside off. Mulder leaves it alone.
A beauty to end the over! It lands outside off, on a length and nips in off the deck. Zondo shoulders his arms at it. Fortunately, it passes over the off pole.
Fuller, on middle and leg. Zondo defends it back to the bowler with full face.
This one is angled into the batter. Zondo hangs back and blocks it out watchfully.
Fuller, sliding down leg. Zondo looks to flick it away but misses. It hits his pads and rolls towards square leg. Ollie Robinson makes a stifled appeal but no interest from the umpire.
FOUR! A much-needed boundary for South Africa. It is a short ball, outside off. Zondo hangs back and crunches it through point for a boundary.
Outside off, left alone by Zondo.
Gets this one to shape away from a length, outside off. Mulder stays back and leaves it alone.
Five dots on the trot for Stokes! An inswinger this time, fuller and on the pads. Mulder gets pinged on his pads. Going down leg.
Angles it in full, around middle and leg. Mulder nudges it to mid-wicket.
Fraction short, going down leg. Mulder looks to pull it away. It hits him on his gloves and meets the keeper on a bounce.
Full length, outside off. Mulder shoulders his arms at it.
The pressure keeps on growing with these dots balls. Stokes dishes a length ball, outside off, nipping away off the deck. Mulder watches it sail past him.
Much fuller, on middle and leg. Zondo flicks it to mid-wicket. A maiden to start with for Robinson.
Play and a miss! It is outside off, on a length, no movement off the seam this time. Zondo looks to have a poke at it with any foot movement, only to get beaten on the outside edge.
Fuller in length, outside off. This time it shapes in off the deck. Zondo shoulders his arms at it.
A length ball, in the channel. It takes an inside edge and goes to the slip cordon.
Back of a length, wide of off, shaping away. Zondo does not go after it this time.
A length ball, outside off, this one stays a touch low. Zondo swings wildly and gets beaten on the inside edge.
Change. Ollie Robinson comes back into the attack now.
Make it 5! Full length, attacking the stumps. Mulder blocks it out watchfully. Just a single off the over then. It like South Africa have walked into a brick wall here.
Four dots in a row! A short one this time, on middle. Mulder swivels and pulls it to the man at square leg. Mulder could not time it well here.
Length ball, down leg. Mulder fails to tickle it away. Goes straight into the keeper's mitts.
On a length, outside off, shaping away a touch. Mulder does not bother at all.
A yorker length delivery, on off. Mulder gets his blade down in time and dabs it out to backward point.
Zondo taps this full delivery to point for a single.

Drinks break! England seamers have done the trick in the post-Lunch session so far. They have dried up the run flow and have taken timely wickets as well. They will be hoping to take a couple more wicket to put the opposition under pressure here. South Africa need their batters to focus on building stands and keep the runs ticking if they are to make anything from the match. An intriguing session of play awaits.
It is fuller, sliding down leg. Mulder misses his flick. It brushes his pads and goes towards the keeper. They appeal for caught behind but the umpire shows no interest.
Good length, outside off. Mulder looks to chase it but misses. The ball sneaks past the inside edge.
Back of a length, outside off. Mulder gets on top of it and cuts it through point. They take two runs. 100 is up for South Africa now.
Touch fuller, on middle and leg. Zondo flicks it to square leg for a single.
A length ball, outside off, shaping into the batter. Zondo gets an inside edge onto the pads.
Zondo defends this length delivery to covers off the outer half.
In the channel, moving away. Mulder blocks it out to safety.
Khaya Zondo is finally off the mark here. It is fuller, on off. Zondo defends it gently towards covers and scampers across for a quick single. This should get him going.
Shorter, outside off. Zondo gets on top of the bounce and works it to backward point. Not in the gap.
A length ball, around off, shaping away. Zondo gets it to the left of fourth slip. Ollie Pope dives to that side and makes a great stop.
Good length, outside off, shaping away a touch. Zondo leaves it alone for the keeper.
Full length, on off. Zondo opens the face and guides it to point.
Change. Ben Stokes comes into the attack now.
Much straighter, outside off. Mulder lets it be. A maiden now for Broad.
It is full, nipping in from outside off. Mulder gets beaten on the inside edge to get pinged high on his pads.
Fuller, on off, defended to covers.
Much fuller, moving down leg. Mulder looks to flick it but misses. Ben Foakes dives to his left and makes a sharp stop.
Full length, on middle. Mulder pushes it to mid on.
This one lands outside off and nips in. Mulder hangs back and defends it out solidly.
LEG BYE! On a length, swinging down leg. Mulder misses his flick. It goes to the leg side off his pads. They collect a leg bye. The runs are coming in at a very slow rate here for the Proteas.
An inswinger full and on off. Mulder gets it to slip cordon off the outer half.
Fuller, outside off. Mulder leans in and pushes it to covers.
A lot of movement! It lands full around off, and nips away sharply off the deck. Wiaan Mulder does not offer any stroke.
In the channel of uncertainty. Mulder looks to block it away but does so inside the line.
Touch fuller, outside off, left alone.
Fuller, on fourth stump. Zondo gets behind and bunts it out to safety.
Outside off, shaping in a touch late. Zondo shoulders his arms at it.
A length ball, sliding down leg. It brushes his thigh pads and goes to the left of the keeper.
Fuller, on the stumps. Mulder gets it to square leg off the inner half. They take one. Mulder is off the mark.
Full length, outside off. Mulder comes down the track and defends it to the left of the bowler.
Much straighter, wide of off, on a length. Mulder leaves it alone for the keeper.
On a length, outside off. Zondo is a bit late to make his leave. It goes to the slip cordon off the bottom half. Luckily, it meets the fielder on a bounce.
A length ball, around off, it nips in off the deck. Zondo fails to flick it away. He gets pinged on his pads. Going down leg.
Fuller, wide of off, shaping away. Zondo reaches out and gets it to the slip cordon off the outer half.
Length ball, at the stumps now. Zondo opens the face and eases it to point.
And again! Khaya Zondo leaves his bat hanging inside the line just to be beaten on the outside edge.
Nicely bowled! It is a length ball, around off. It moves away off the deck. Khaya Zondo looks to defend it out but gets beaten past the outside edge.
Full, just outside off. Mulder stays back and defends it to the off side watchfully.
An inswinger full and on off. Mulder blocks it into the deck.
Wiaan Mulder comes in at number 6.

OUT! LBW! This time he raps him on the pads without the inside edge. Stuart Broad appeals and the umpire raises his finger in a flash. Ryan Rickelton has a chat with his partner and takes the review. Coming to the delivery. It is full, around middle, straightens a touch off the deck and hits him on his pads. The UltraEdge confirms no bat is involved. Commentary.Commentary: Stuart Broad steams in and hurls a full delivery, fired into off. Ryan Rickelton gets an inside edge onto his pads.
Broad angles it in outside off from 'round the wicket and gets it to shape away off the deck. Ryan Rickelton watches it sail past him.
Much fuller, outside off. Ryan Rickelton leaves it alone for the keeper.
On a length, in the channel, moving away a touch. Zondo lets it be.
Fuller, on off. Zondo drives it to cover-point where Alex Lees makes a sharp stop.
Inswinger full and on off. Zondo defends it to covers.
On off, blocked out.
Another dot now! Full length, outside off, shaping away sharply. Zondo leaves it alone.
On a length, outside off. Zondo stays back and blocks it out.
Length ball, outside off, gets it to shape away yet again. Ryan Rickelton isn't tempted at all.
Touch fuller, outside off, it shapes away off the deck. Ryan Rickelton watches it sail past him.
Swinging away, wide of off. Ryan Rickelton has no shot to offer.
This is full, on off. Ryan Rickelton gets on his front foot and blocks it back to the bowler.
Good length, wide of off. Ryan Rickelton lets it be.
FOUR! Excellent shot! It is an outswinging delivery, wide outside off. Ryan Rickelton picks up pretty early and drills it through covers for a boundary.
Full length, outside off, shaping away. Khaya Zondo gets an outside edge to third slip along the ground.
Outside off, left alone.
Good length, comes in from outside off. Zondo leaves it alone bravely.

OUT! CAUGHT! James Anderson finds a breakthorugh now. It is a length ball, outside off, moving away off the deck. Keegan Petersen looks to push it away but only gets a thick outside edge. Ollie Pope at fourth slip dives forward and takes a brilliant catch. South Africa lose their second wicket in the afternoon session. Khaya Zondo is the new man in.

Commentary.Commentary: Touch fuller, outside off, shaping away. Petersen stays back and works it to point.
Back of a length, around off. Keegan Petersen comes forward and taps it to cover.
It is full, drifting down leg. Ryan Rickelton misses his flick. Just a single off the over then.
Length, angled across the left-hander, it is in the channel. Ryan Rickelton keeps his bat to himself.
An inswinger this time, full and on the pads. Keegan Petersen flicks it to mid on for a single.
Good length, outside off, left alone by Keegan Petersen.
Fuller, on the pads. Keegan Petersen looks to flick it away but gets it to covers off the leading edge.
A dot now! Full length, shaping in around off. Keegan Petersen presses forward and blocks it back to the bowler.
On a length, outside off, angled across. Ryan Rickelton leaves it alone for the keeper.
It is full, swinging into the pads. Keegan Petersen flicks it through mid-wicket. The batters take three with ease.
A length ball, outside off. Keegan Petersen leaves it alone.
Pace up this time. Good length, wide of off, nips in a long way. Keegan Petersen trusts the bounce and shoulders his arms at it.
Touch fuller, on middle and leg. Keegan Petersen tucks it to the leg side.
Anderson pitches it outside off and gets it to nip back in sharply. Keegan Petersen gets pinged on his thigh pads.
FOUR! This is banged in short and wide, Ryan Rickelton slaps it up and over the cover region and opens his account with a boundary.
Length ball, around leg stump, Ryan Rickelton works it away onto the leg side.
Ryan Rickelton comes in at number 4.

OUT! LBW! This time Stuart Broad does get his man! Broad goes fuller and angling into the pads. Dean Elgar looks to flick it away but falls over and ends up playing all around it. The ball crashes into the pads and Elgar starts walking even before the finger is raised. England do have the prozed wicket of the South African skipper and they will look to build on it. The replays show that the ball was going down leg and Elgar will be very disappointed as he didn't even think about reviewing it. England have got away with one here.
Commentary.Howout: lbw b Stuart Broad

Commentary.Commentary: Length again and angling onto the pads as well. Elgar misses the flick and gets hit on the knee roll.
Length again, around middle, worked away onto the leg side.
A big appeal for lbw but it looks to be too high. This is angled in from around the wicket and on the pads. Dean Elgar looks to defend but misses and gets hit high on the pads.
A couple of dots to end the over, 5 runs come off it. On a fuller length and around off, Petersen leaves it alone.
Length ball, around off and this one leaves the batter off the deck. Keegan Petersen shoulders arms at it.
Pitches it up now, in that channel around off, Petersen makes a watchful leave.
FOUR! Keegan Petersen is on fire at the moment. Good length, around off, Petersen rocks onto the back foot and punches it through extra cover for a glorious boundary.
On a length and outside off, there's a bit of movement in the air this time. Petersen has a dab at it but the ball zips past the outside edge.
Anderson starts from around the wicket and angles it in around the hips. Dean Elgar neatly flicks it down to fine leg and collects a run.
It will be James Anderson to bowl from the other end.
FOUR! Up and over! Short and wide, Keegan Petersen throws his hands at it and gets it over the leaping fielder at point for yet another boundary.
Length ball, pushed wide of the off stump. Keegan Petersen just watches the ball go past him and into the keeper's mitts.
Shortish ball, on the body, Petersen hops and defends it back onto the deck.
FOUR! Back of a length from Broad and there's width on offer as well. Keegan Petersen stays back and slaps it away through the point region for a boundary.
Edged but safe! Fullish length, outside off, Petersen looks to play it out with soft hands but gets an outside edge down towards the man at fourth slip.
Broad starts off with a length ball, around the top of off and staying a touch low. Keegan Petersen keeps it out on the off side.

We are back for the afternoon session at the Oval. England players stride out to the middle. Followed by Keegan Petersen and Dean Elgar who walk out with their blades. It will be Stuart Broad to start with the ball now. Here we go...
... Day 4, Session 2 ...

Just like we expected, there is not much venom on the pitch for the seamers. It was clear as England struggled to find an early breakthrough this morning. They hardly got the batters into trouble. There were some close chances but the lady luck wasn't on their side. The skipper then got himself into the attack and broke a crucial stand that was taking the game away from them. England still have a stiff challenge ahead of them. They will be hoping to make an instant impression in the post-Lunch session. Do join us at 6.10 pm IST (12.40 pm GMT) to find out how things pan out.

It was 'do or die' time for the Proteas as they came out to bat early on Day 4 and had to put on a sizeable score on the board for a side that certainly loves to chase in the final innings of a Test match in the new era. Dean Elgar and Sarel Erwee came out and took their time to settle-in. The opening pair built a solid foundation up top which was missing in this Test match for South Africa. Sarel Erwee slipped out just before the Lunch break. Keegan Petersen though came in and handled the situation well at one end. Dean Elgar is the key for the visitors and they would hope he can take it deep. South Africa head into the break with a lead of 30 runs.

A session that was dominated by the visitors throughout. On the morning of Day 4 it was South Africa that came out guns blazing. The pair of Rabada and Jansen took just 16 deliveries to bundle out England for 158. Although, later England could not apply the same pressure with the ball as they did in the first innings and see themselves chasing the game at the moment.
A dot to end! fullish length, in that channel around off and Dean Elgar plays inside the line this time. That will be Lunch on Day 4!
This is angled into the pads from around the wicket. Elgar misses the flick and the ball goes off the pads towards short leg.
Length ball, around off, Keegan Petersen takes a couple of steps towards the ball and pushes it down the ground. Stuart Broad chases it down from mid-wicket and saves a run for his side.
Nicely bowled! Pitched up, around off and angling in. The ball just holds its line and beats the outside edge.
On a good length and on off, Robinson gets a bit of extra bounce due to his height and Petersen does well to keep it down on the off side.
The bowler goes up in appeal for lbw but no one else is interested. Good length, around off and nipping back in. Keegan Petersen gets a big inside edge onto the pads as he looks to defend it out.
FOUR! Poor delivery from Ben Stokes and Dean Elgar puts it away with ease. This is a half-volley, around the pads and Elgar clips it away in front of square on the leg side for a boundary.
Full and angling well down the leg side, Ben Foakes does well to dive to his right and make the stop.
Here comes the change up! This is a well-directed bumper by Stokes, over middle and Dean Elgar does well to sway his head away from it.
Stokes keeps bowling it full and at the stumps, Elgar wrists it towards the man at mid-wicket.
Full and straight, Elgar pushes it firmly towards mid on.
Very full and at the t0oes, clipped away towards square leg.
Leg bye! Fuller in length and angling down leg, Elgar looks to flick but the ball hits the back leg and rolls towards square leg. They do get across for a leg bye.
Fuller and attacking the pads, Elgar looks to work it away but misses.
Robinson hurls across a length ball from around the wickets and bowls it close to the off pole. Dean Elgar shoulders arms at it.
This is full and wide, Keegan Petersen reaches out and times it nicely through point. A couple of fielders chase after it and the batters get back for the third with ease.
Good length, around off and left alone by Petersen.
Nicely bowled! Ollie Robinson serves it on a length and in that channel around off, the ball nips away a touch as well. Keegan Petersen just feels for the ball but gets beaten past the outside edge.
Pitched up in that channel around off and Dean Elgar makes a comfortable leave.
Back to around the wicket now for Elgar and this is a full ball on middle. Elgar manages to jam it out.
Shorter and around off, Keegan Petersen waits for it and just eases it towards cover-point for a single.
Keegan Petersen walks in at number 3.

OUT! CAUGHT! A masterstroke by the skipper Ben Stokes and he breaks the opening stand. Stokes continues from over the wicket and just angles across a very full ball. This is around off and Sarel Erwee gets suckered into driving at it. The outside edge is found and Joe Root at first slip takes a really good catch diving forward. The catch is a clean one and South Africa have lost their first wicket.
Commentary.Howout: c Joe Root b Ben Stokes

Commentary.Commentary: Switches to over the wicket now and serves a length ball on off. Sarel Erwee gets on the front foot and defends it out onto the off side.
Stokes starts off with a shortish ball from around the wicket. The ball jags back in sharply off the deck. Dean Elgar awkwardly gets it away behind point and collects a single.
Change. Ben Stokes gets himself into the attack now.
End of a maiden over by Ollie Robinson. On a hard length, around middle, Sarel Erwee looks to play it off the back foot but once again the inside edge is found.
Good length, on leg stump, Erwee looks to defend but gets an inside edge onto the pads.
Length ball, around leg stump and this is punched to the man at mid on.
Fuller and angling it across the left-hander, left alone for the keeper to collect.
Pitches it up now, on off and Erwee solidly defends it off the front foot.
Robinson starts off the new spell from over the wicket and bowls it on a good length, close to the off pole. Sarel Erwee leaves it alone.
Change. Ollie Robinson (5-1-16-0) is back on now.
Anderson pulls back the length a bit and angles it in from around off. Dean Elgar makes an assured leave.
Very full, around middle and leg and pushed towards silly mid on.
FOUR! James Anderson angles this one down the leg side, Dean Elgar just about gets some bat on it and the ball runs away fine, into the fence.

England aren't happy with the ball here. This is the second time they have asked the umpire to get 8-ball gauge out and yet again it passes through with ease. England are desperate to break this opening stand of South Africa.
This one is angled into leg stump, Dean Elgar defends it out with a straight bat.
Goes fuller now and attacks the stumps, Elgar stays watchful and keeps it out.
On a fullish length but well wide of the off stump, Elgar has nothing to do with it.
Pitches it up now, close to the off pole and Erwee lets it through to the keeper.
Good length, slanted in from around off, Erwee makes a watchful leave.
A touch fuller and angling into middle and leg. Sarel Erwee stands tall and just punches it past mid on for a couple of runs.
Keeps it fuller and around middle, clipped away towards mid-wicket.

FOUR! Full and straight from Broad, Sarel Erwee gets inside the line of the ball and flicks it fine. The ball races away into the fine leg fence. The 50 is up for South Africa and they will be delighted with this start.
Short of a length and well outside off, Erwee leaves it alone.

Beaten! Half an appeal for a caught-behind but the umpire remains unmoved. Anderson serves it on a perfect length, close to the off pole and just shaping away. Dean Elgar looks to defend but gets beaten past the outside edge. There is a noise but that of the bat hitting the pad.
Fuller and around middle, just straightening off the deck. Erwee defends it towards the cover region and picks up a single.
On a nagging length, angling in sharply from around off. Sarel Erwee does well to keep this one out.
Pitched up, around off and this is pushed away towards the cover region. The throw comes in at the striker's end and it is a wide one, allowing the batters to get across for a single.
Anderson keeps it full and around the pads, Elgar awkwardly nudges it away towards square leg.

Oh, my! James Anderson comes back into the attack and serves it full and around the pads. The ball nips away sharply and Dean Elgar gets taken aback. The ball takes the outside edge and falls short of the slip cordon.

Drinks break! The morning session on Day 4 has completely belonged to the Proteas. They were brilliant with the ball and now with the bat, the openers, Dean Elgar and Sarel Erwee have looked solid and have even managed to surpass the English lead. They will look to carry on in the same way. England are currently suffering from a setback and it will be interesting to see how they respond to it, otherwise, they could slip further in this game.
FOUR! Shorter and wider from Broad, Erwee hangs back and just steers it behind point for a boundary.
Good length, around off, Sarel Erwee plays inside the line of the ball.
Fuller and outside off, stroked away through cover-point for a single.

Stuart Broad bowls it shorter and angles it into the body. Dean Elgar hops and looks to work it leg side. The ball seems to have popped up off the thigh pad and pouched comfortably by the man at fifth slip. There is a huge appeal for a catch but the umpire turns it down. The English players have a long discussion and at the very last second, Ben Stokes opts to review it. The Third umpire checks UltraEdge and finds that there are a couple of noises, first the bat hitting the pad and then the ball hitting the pad as well. Great decision by the on-field umpire and Elgar survives.
With that unsuccessul review, England have now lost two reviews which might come back to haunt them later on.
Just a touch fuller and on the fifth stump line, Elgar shoulders arms to it.
On a good length and outside off, shaping away. Dean Elgar leaves it alone.
On a length, outside off, shapes in a bit later. Erwee shoulders his arms at it.
Strays on the pads now. Erwee flicks it to square leg. James Anderson moves to his left and makes a sharp stop. The scores are still level.
Robinson steams in from 'round the wicket and serves it full, outside off. this one moves away a bit. Sarel Erwee looks to defend it out but misses it.
Length ball, on off, defended to covers.
An appeal for caught behind by the fielders from behind the wicket. The bowler shows no interest though. This one brushes his pads on the way to the keeper.
It is a length ball, outside off, angled across. Erwee has no shot to offer.
Length ball, outside off, shaping away. Elgar lets it be.
FOUR! Nicely played! It is a good-length ball, outside off. Dean Elgar opens the face of the blade and guides it past backward point. It has enough legs to reach the ropes. Scores level now.
Elgar punches this length delivery through point. They take two runs.
Full length, angled into the pads, Elgar tucks it to mid-wicket.
Much fuller, outside off, left alone by Elgar.
A short ball, outside off. Elgar pulls it over mid on. He does not time it well and only gets a couple.
Stuart Broad is brought into the attack now. He replaces James Anderson.
Outside off, left alone. South Africa trail by 8 runs now.
FOUR! Good looking shot by Erwee! It is full, straight, on the pads. Erwee flicks it through the gap at mid-wicket and finds the boundary.
Sarel Erwee flicks this good-length delivery off his hips towards deep square leg. The batters take two.
A length ball, around middle and leg. Erwee looks to whip it across the line but misses. It brushes off his thigh pads and rolls to the slip cordon.
Robinson hurls in full and on off. Erwee gets an inside edge on his pads.
Fuller and on off. Elgar gets it to covers off the outer half. They take a single.
So, 5 runs off the over then. It is full and on off. Erwee blocks it back to the bowler.
Good length, angling across the left-hander. Sarel Erwee has no shot to offer.

Anderson angles it in full and on off. Elgar dabs it towards point. A bit of miscommunication but Sarel Erwee makes it safely to the other end. Ben Stokes shows great intent in the field. He charges towards the ball and has a shy at the striker's end with a forward dive. Misses by a mile.
Elgar blocks this length ball watchfully.
FOUR! NIcely played! Back of a length, outside off. Dean Elgar stands tall and cuts it through point. The ball races away.
It is a length ball, outside off. this one straightens a bit after hitting the deck. Elgar looks to chase it but gets beaten.
Good length, outside off. Erwee gets it past backward point. They batters take two.

A huge appeal for lbw but turned down! Ollie Robinson is quite certain that he got his man this time. Ben Stokes takes a review now. It is a length ball, pitching around leg. Erwee looks to defend it out but misses and gets rapped on his pads. The UltraEdge later confirms that no bat is involved. The Ball Tracking shows that the ball is pitching fractionally outside leg and on-field decision stands. England lose a review now.
It is full, on off. Erwee bunts it down the ground. The batters take two before the fielder cuts it out. It is also called as a no ball as the bowler oversteps.
Outside off, left alone.
A length ball, on off. Erwee works it to covers off the outer half.
Good length, around off. Erwee gets across and gets an inside edge on his pads. It rolls out to point.
Short of the fielder! It is full, around off, angling away. Erwee gets it to the left of gully off the outside edge. It meets Anderson on a bounce.
Now beats the outside edge. On a length, on fifth stump. Elgar looks to chase it but misses.

What a beauty! James Anderson cuts the batter in half this time. It is a length ball, around off, nips back in off the deck. Elgar looks to defend and gets beaten on the inside edge. The ball passes over the middle stump here.
James Anderson serves it full, angled in on off. Elgar blocks it into the deck on his front foot.
It is much fuller, wide outside off, this one spits off the deck. Elgar shuffles across and leaves it alone.
A length ball, on off, Elgar blocks it out solidly.
FOUR! Poor delivery and Elgar punishes. It is short, wide of off. Elgar frees his arms and flays it over backward point for a boundary.
Good length, on off, defended back to the bowler.

NOT OUT! A great decision by the umpire. England players did not even look excited it was more of a muted celebration by the hosts. It is a full-length ball, on off. Erwee looks to flick it away but is a bit early into his shot. It goes towards gully off the leading edge. The ball stays low and James Anderson there has to bend forward and eventually gathers it on a bounce. It is later confirmed by the third umpire as well, as the umpires took it upstairs.

Is that a clean catch? James Anderson seems to have taken a good low catch here but he isn't sure. The two umpires come together for a chat and go upstairs. The soft signal is NOT OUT. The third umpire checks it a couple of times and concludes that the ball clearly bounced before going into the palms of Anderson.
Length ball, on middle and leg. Erwee shuffles and flicks it to mid-wicket.
On off, defended out watchfully.
It is a length ball, on off. Erwee gets it through covers and takes two.
A stifled appeal for lbw and the umpire shows no interest! It is a length ball, that lands around leg and hits Erwee on his thigh pads. It looks to be high.
Touch fuller, outside off. Elgar lets it be. 5 runs off the over then.
Length ball, on off, defended out solidly.
FOUR! Fortunate boundary for Elgar. It is a short ball, outside off, seaming away. Dean Elgar gets it past gully off the outer half. It races away. First boundary for South Africa.
Length, on off. Erwee taps it to covers and scampers for a quick single.
Touch fuller, around off, angling away. Erwee looks to block it but does so inside the line.
On middle and leg, flicked to the man at square leg.
This one is on a length, in the channel. Elgar looks to chase it but gets beaten past the outside edge.
Fuller, on off. Elgar blocks it to the leg side watchfully.
On off, defended out.
BEAUTY! It is a length ball, around off, it shapes away after hitting the deck. Elgar looks to block it out but puts his blade down in the end.
Full length, at the stumps. Elgar presses forward and defends it back to the bowler.
Dean Elgar opens his account with a brace here. Robinson comes 'round the wicket and angles it in full and on off. Elgar stays back and flicks it to deep square leg for two runs.
Ollie Robinson to operate from the opposite end.
Just two runs off the over then! Full length, outside off. Erwee leans in and drives it crisply towards covers. Cannot find the gap though.
Make that three! Good length, in the channel, shaping away with the angle. Erwee has no shot to offer.
Second dot on the trot! On a length, angled across the left-hander, wide of off. Sarel Erwee shoulders his arms at it.
Good length, on middle and leg. Erwee blocks it to the leg side.
A length ball, on off this time. Erwee gets an inside edge and the ball runs down to fine leg. They take two. Sarel Erwee and South Africa are off the mark here.
James Anderson starts with a length ball, outside off, shaping away. Erwee leaves it alone.

That's it then from the series as Ben Stokes is presented with the series trophy and the entire England squad joins him for a team photograph. It is also the end of the English summer as well as far as international cricket is concerned. Both teams now move on to new ventures before heading into the T20 World Cup a month or so later. England travel to Pakistan to play a 7-match T20I series starting the 20th of September. As for the Proteas, they will head home and then to India for a white-ball series that will begin on the 28th of September. Join us for all the action from those series. Until next time, take care and goodbye!

English skipper, Ben Stokes is the ENGLISH PLAYER OF THE SERIES for his brilliant all-round show. He says that it has been a great series where they didn't have any particular single individual performing but it was a team performance. Further says that the conditions they found out on Day 1 after the toss and they were better on the 3rd day and toss plays a major role. Adds that when you have got bowlers like James Anderson and Stuart Broad it's great that they can have small spells and stay fresh and they have been absolutely phenomenal. Adds that if they are winning six of seven games because of their aggressive gameplay, then they don't mind playing that way. Adds that they are clearly giving the message the way they are going to play and the coach also supports them. Their main moto was to find the result in the last match. Further, says it's very important to give proper time to payers like Ollie Pope and it shows how important it is to let them play their game. Mentions that the opening batters give a good momentum and that eases pressure on the lower order. James Anderson is also a player they can rely on and he is always up for the challenge. Adds that Joe Root should also be given credit for how he had kept the team for 6 years and for that he is very grateful and each captain has his own style. Ends by saying that it will be challenging to play against Pakistan and more spin will come into play but they are up for it.

Dean Elgar, the skipper of South Africa is down for a chat. He says that it hasn't been great for him in an international game in Oval. Informs that first innings runs are very important in England and they failed to get those. Mentions they just tried to utilize the bench strength. Adds they were put in very tough conditions in a tough match but they will surely take a lot of learnings from it. Mentions if you apply yourself as a batter, it would get easy for sure but it also relies on the execution of the plans. Says that he is an advocate when it comes to Test matches. "More the merrier", he says. He thinks that England played excellent cricket and added pressure by putting enough runs on the board.

Kagiso Rabada is the SOUTH AFRICAN PLAYER OF THE SERIES for picking up 14 wickets in the series, including a match-winning spell at Lord's. He says that they won the toss at Lord's and the toss proved to be crucial in all three games. Further, says that they are a young side including himself and will learn a lot of things and take this as a lesson. Adds that was he injured during a T20 match earlier in the series but recovered well and played the Test series. Further, says that leading the bowling with young guns is always a pleasure and ends by saying that one could feel good in the nets but not the same on the field but what matters is to find to perform regardless of how one feels.

Ollie Robinson (7 for 89) is the PLAYER OF THE MATCH for his exceptional spell with the ball. He says that it has been a really enjoyable comeback for him and the team over the summer. Adds that he doesn't feel like he is an finished article by any means, he still has a long way to go and will keep improving. Says they are thriving under the leadership of Stokes and it feels really nice. Ends by saying he is really happy for his contribution.
As the English cricketing summer comes to an end, Jonny Bairstow has been declared as the 'PLAYER OF THE TEST SUMMER.'
The presentation ceremony...

Earlier in the game, Ben Stokes won the toss and opted to bowl first but we did not have any cricketing action on the first couple of days of the Test match. Once play did resume on the morning of Day 3, Ollie Robinson ripped through the South African batting order as he picked up a five-wicket haul and Stuart Broad picked up four wickets as well. The South African batting order was in disarray as one of their frontline bowlers, Marco Jansen top-scored with 30 runs. The pitch had enough in it for the pacers and after a sedate start, the visiting team showed its prowess with the ball and Jansen was at the forefront of it all once again. He too picked up a five-fer and Kagiso Rabada managed to clean up the tail. With the game hanging right in the balance, the tide started to turn but once again the visitors were hard done by their inexperienced batters. The English pacers, once they got a sniff, did really well with skipper Ben Stokes picking up wickets at crucial stages of the game. In reply, England needed 130 runs to win and they chased it down with utmost ease. Stay tuned for the presentation...

South Africa were impressive in the white-ball phase of this tour and they continued that momentum as they won the first Test of this series with a big margin as well. It all went downhill in the second Test and the changes made for the final Test haven't proved to be effective at all. Their batting was a mess in the first innings and their bowlers didn't start off well either. Marco Jansen though looked good with the ball and gave them renewed hope in the first innings. The visitors did manage to keep the English lead to a minimum and had a fantastic start with the bat as well in the second innings. The turning point was probably Dean Elgar not opting to review an lbw decision when he was looking so good. After that, there was a collapse and their pacers didn't create enough opportunities in the final innings, which meant it was yet another defeat and from leading the series 1-0, they ended up losing it.

It was a bit of a topsy-turvy game with pacers from both teams dominating but it has been the batting from England that has made a bigger difference. It wasn't particularly impressive apart from Ollie Pope in the first innings but during the chase, both openers were able to just play their shots and get their team ahead in the game. Zak Crawley was mighty impressive as he scored a brilliant half-century and even though Alex Lees edged a few, he rode his luck and gave ample support to Crawley as well. Lees did get out towards the end but Ollie Pope came in and ensured that his side won the game at the earliest. It proved to be a straightforward chase in the end as the conditions had gotten brighter and the pitch didn't have enough bite in it.

What a grandstand finish we have had to a grandstand Test series! This wasn't what one would call a classic Test series but within less than 9 complete days of play, we have had results in all three games of the series. As expected it hasn't taken much time for the English batters to notch up the remaining 33 runs and they have sealed a memorable Test series win as they clinch the series 2-1. It has been a brilliant English summer from the point of view of Test cricket and they have finished off the home season with a deserving victory over the Proteas.
FOUR! Zak Crawley gets the winning runs here. It is a length ball, outside off. Zak Crawley hangs back and punches it through covers. It races away to the fence and England win by 9 wickets.
Fuller length, down the leg. Zak Crawley lets that one go through to the keeper.
Fuller, on middle and leg. Ollie Pope pushes it towards the square leg for a run.

Rabada attacking the stumps yet again. Crawley is solid in his defence.
A length ball, on off, stump. Zak Crawley blocks it with full face.

NO BALL! Zak Crawley tries something new! That was full, on off. Zak Crawley tries to switch hits it over the slips but gets an upper edge and the ball hits his chin. Hopefully, he is ok.

Fuller length, outside off. Ollie Pope pushes it towards cover.
On a good length, on off. Ollie Pope blocks off the front foot.

Lees drives this full delivery to backward point as it goes off the outer half.

Length and outside off. Crawley lets it go.
LEG BYE! It is full, drifting down leg. Lees looks to flick it away but misses. It goes down to third man off his pads. They cross for a leg bye.
Outside off, left alone.
Fuller, down leg. Lees looks to chase it but misses.

FOUR! Alex Lees is riding on his luck this morning. It is a length ball, outside off, shaping away. Lees gets a thick outside edge on it. It flies over Keegan Petersen at the third slip, although he is a bit late in picking up the ball. It flies over him and races away to the third man fence.

Marco Jansen (5-0-24-0) to operate from the other end.
Fuller, on off. Zak Crawley defends it out solidly.
Good length, outside off. Crawley looks to chase it but misses.
Length ball, around off. Zak Crawley drives it into covers for two runs now.

Run straightaway for England and Zak Crawley. It is full, straying on the pads. Zak Crawley flicks it to fine leg and crosses for one.

We are ready for the start of play on Day 5! The umpires are already out in the middle and so are the players of South Africa. Zak Crawley and Alex Lees are the overnight batters for England. It will be Kagiso Rabada to start off proceedings with the ball this morning. Let's play...

South Africa dominated the morning session on Day 4 both with bat and ball and the game was well poised at that moment. The English seamers remained patient and cashed-in in the post-Lunch session when there was some movement on offer. The Proteas ended up setting up a target of just 130 runs and the England openers rose to the occasion. Zak Crawley smacked his first Test fifty of this summer for England,  a much-needed knock for him after facing a lot of criticism . They are coming into Day 5 to hunt down just 33 runs with 10 wickets in hand. Shouldn't be long before they seal the series and their summer on a high.

Hello and a warm welcome to all! It now time for Day 5 of the third and the final Test match between England and South Africa. We only got 3 days of play as Day 1 got washed out due to rain and Day 2 was called off to pay respect to the sad demise of Her Majesty Queen Elizabeth II. So, out of the 9 sessions in hand, it looks like we will only require 7 sessions to get a result on our hands. Throughout this Test series we have never played for whole 5 days.
... Day 5, Session 1 ...

Right then, the match is getting to its final stage and so is the long Test series. We have had just a couple of days of cricketing action but it has been thoroughly entertaining. The match did swing both ways before England grabbed the bull by its horns and have more or less sealed the game. They require 33 more runs to win and they will look to finish off proceedings early on Day 5. Day 5 action will begin at 3.30 pm IST (10 am GMT) but you can join us sooner for the build-up. Cheers!

South Africa will be really disappointed with how Day 4 started and how it has eventually ended. They looked good in the first session but that was it. The next two sessions were difficult for them and they have let the game slip with both bat and ball. Their inexperienced middle order never looked up for the task and were undone by simple yet effective bowling by the English pacers. Onto the bowling then and Kagiso Rabada's poor form continued as he was all over the place. Rabada did create an opportunity early on but his compatriot with the new ball, Marco Jansen spilled it and after that, it was all England. The visitors have been treated to some great batting by the English openers and had no answers in return.

That's it then! The umpires have decided that the light is not good enough for the play to continue and Stumps have been called. With just 33 runs required for England to seal the series, we will go into the fifth day. This has been an utterly dominating display by the English openers and they have made sure that their team does not suffer any sort of mishaps late in the day. Zak Crawley and Alex Lees have looked brilliant from ball one and barring a couple of chances early in the innings, have remained largely untroubled.

FOUR! England are fighting with time here to end the game before any evidence of bad light. Alex Lees is on a mission to end things in a hurry. It is full, wide outside off. A single now as this is flicked through mid-wicket.
Length ball, on off, defended to covers.

A length ball,on off, blocked out.
Around middle, flicked away down to fine leg for a single.
Back of a length and around off, eased off the back foot towards cover.

Good length, around off, played away towards backward point.

Pitches it up now, around off, Alex Lees swings at it but does not connect.
Good length, around off, left alone by the batter.
Length ball, pushed outside off by Nortje, the keeper does well to dive to his left and collect the ball.

Length, around off. Lees gets it back to the bowler.
Good length, on fifth stump. Lees hangs back and punches it through point. They take two runs.
A great over by Kagiso Rabada comes to an end. It is a short ball, outside off. Zak Crawley stands tall and looks to pull it away but only connects with thin air.
It is full, on middle and leg. Zak Crawley comes down the track and looks to flick it away. It rolls to the off side off his pads.
Back of a length, around off. Crawley comes down the track and pulls it hard to square leg only to find the fielder.
A length ball, at the stumps. Crawley blocks it to the leg side off the inner half.
LEG BYE! This one comes into the batter from outside off. Lees gets hit high on his pads. They collect a leg bye.
It is full, angled into middle. Lees blocks it past the bowler with a straight bat.
Back of a length, on the bodyline. Lees flicks it to deep mid-wicket for a single.
It is fuller and on middle and leg, Lees misses his flick and it rolls out off his pads.
On off, pushed out to safety.

A short ball, on off. It flies off the deck. Alex Lees hangs back and looks to defend it with full face of the blade. The ball though chips in front of him off the shoulder of the blade. No trouble here.
Fuller, on off, blocked back to the bowler.
NO BALL! A short ball, on off. Zak Crawley comes down the track a touch and pushes it to mid off. They take one. The umpire signals a no ball for overstepping.
This one lands on a length, around off. It nips back in off the deck. Zak Crawley gets pinged high on his thigh pads.
Length and at the stumps. Lees blocks it out.
Outside off, left alone.
Rabada serves it into the pads, Lees misses his defence and takes a hit on his pads.
Angled in on a length, into the off stump. Lees hangs back and blocks it to the off side.
This one nips back in from outside off. Lees gets pinged on his thigh pads.
Crawley looks to flick it to the leg side but gets it through covers off the leading edge for one.
Much fuller, in the channel. Lees presses forward and deals with it.
A quick bouncer, on middle. Lees sways away from the line. Kyle Verreynne leaps behind the sticks and grabs it one hand over his head.
Good length, around off. Lees pushes it to covers with soft hands.
Fuller, on off, blocked back to the bowler.
This is angled into the pads. Lees nurdles it to mid-wicket.
Length ball, on the pads. Zak Crawley flicks it to deep square leg for a single.
Rabada goes shorter and bowls it outside off, Alex Lees lets it through to the keeper.
Fullish delivery, outside off, driven through covers for a single.
Good length again, over middle, Crawley defends it back onto the deck.
Good length, angling in from around off, Zak Crawley gets an inside edge onto the pads.
Length ball, around off, Lees hangs back and pushes it out onto the off side for a single.
Good length, well outside off, driven on the up and through covers for a single.
Play and a miss! good length, around the top of off, Alex Lees looks to play at it but is well beaten.
This one is flicked to mid-wicket for a single.

Just over the fielder! Alex Lees is living dangerously. It is a short ball, wide outside off. Lees looks to pull it away. It takes the outside edge and lobs over mid on. Keshav Maharaj back-pedals, stretches his left arm out but the ball lands wider. They take one.
Full length, on off. Lees gets under it and lofts it over mid off. The batters take two.
Length, around off, defended out.
Fuller and around off, defended out towards cover.
Around off, played away onto the off side for a single.
Good length, around off, this is tapped away towards cover-point for a run.
FOUR! Back-to-back boundaries! Pitched up around middle and leg, gloriously driven by Crawley and straight down the ground for another boundary.
FOUR! Easily done! Shorter and there's width on offer, Zak Crawley stands tall and strokes it away through cover-point for a boundary.
Angling into the pads, flicked away through mid-wicket for a single.
Beaten! Rabada comes from around the wicket and angles it in from around off. The ball straightens off the deck and beats then outside edge.
Around the hips, tucked away towards mid-wicket for a single.
FOUR! Firmly driven! Overpitched on middle, Alex Lees leans in and drives it straight back past the bowler for a boundary.

There is an appeal for a catch but the umpire remains unmoved. Dean Elgar does go upstairs for the review. This is on a good length from Marco Jansen and angling into middle stump. Alex Lees looks to work it away but misses. The ball goes off the thigh pads and it is caught in the slip cordon. The replays show that there is no bat on it and Lees survives yet again.
Fuller and on off stump, defended back towards the bowler.

NOT OUT! A tight single but Alex Lees survives. Length ball, on the pads, Zak Crawley drops it down towards short leg and sets off for the quick single. The fielder at square leg runs in and throws it back onto the stumps at the striker's end. The decision is sent upstairs and we can see that the stretch has saved Lees.
Is that a run out? The umpire takes it upstairs. The replays confirm that Alex Lees had his bat grounded when the bails were off. The big screen shows NOT OUT.
FOUR! Nicely driven! This is pitched up on off stump, Zak Crawley drives it straight back past the bowler and picks up a boundary.
Marco Jansen to bowl from the other end.
Around the pads, clipped away towards mid-wicket.
Length again from Rabada, Crawley stands tall and drives it past the man at point for three runs.
Good length, close to the off pole, Zak Crawley has a dab at it but gets beaten past the outside edge.
On the pads, flicked away onto the leg side.
Length, around off, Zak Crawley lets it through to the keeper.

EDGED AND DROPPED! Kagiso Rabada starts off with a length ball, in that channel around off. Alex Lees pushes at it and gets a thick outside edge. Marco Jansen at fourth slip puts it down and the ball runs away towards third man. They come back for the third.
